d Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17447\n| date = 1920-03-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200417.2.80.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then on May 10 the [[New Zealand Rugby League|New Zealand Rugby League Council]] granted him an open transfer to play in Australia as reported in the ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/The New Zealand Council\n| page = 6\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17467\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200511.2.96.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The ''[[Auckland Star]]'' suggesting that he \u201cwill probably play in Australia\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Affairs in Wellington/N.Z. Council Meets\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LI, Issue 112\n| date = 1920-05-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19200511.2.96\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. It is however unclear as to where he went and if he played rugby league over the following years.\n\n===North Shore Albions===\nIn 1925 Haddon resumed playing rugby league in Auckland, this time however he was to represent the [[North Shore Albions]] who at this time were in fact named [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] after amalgamating with the Sunnyside League Football Club at the start of the 1920 season <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Two Clubs Amalgamate\n| page =6\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVII| issue=17436\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200405.2.100\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. The first mention of him in a Devonport uniform is in a match against his old [[City Rovers]] team at [[Carlaw Park]] where he scored a try <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Another Great Game/City Beat Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 133,\n| date = 1925-06-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250608.2.147\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The day was significant for other reasons as the teams stood in silence before the kick off out of respect for [[Bill Stormont]] (Kiwi #140) who had died two days earlier. In a July match Haddon scored a try in front of 9,000 spectators at Carlaw Park against [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]. Devonport won but not before Haddon was sent off along with Marist\u2019s New Zealand international [[Andrew O'Brien (rugby league)|Jim O'Brien]] after a \u201crough-up\u201d between the two. Devonport won the match 19-11 <ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Code/Devonport\u2019s Day Out/Marists v Devonport\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 145\n| date = 1925-06-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250622.2.108\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nAfter a July match between Ponsonby and Devonport it was said of Haddon \u201cit is surprising how youth sticks to some footballers. On Saturday the veteran \u2026 was easily Devonport\u2019s best forward. He showed a lot of pace and some of the form displayed several years ago when playing for [[City Rovers|City]]\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football Notes and Comments/The North Shore Players\n| page =6 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19069\n| date = 1925-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250714.2.9.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. Then against Athletic \u201cHaddon, following up fast secured, and beating several Athletic players, scored behind the posts with three men hanging on to him\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Club Competitions/Athletic v Devonport\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVI, Issue 169\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19250720.2.137\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. He scored a second try later in the match after a \u201cpassing rush\u201d in which all the Devonport players took part. Haddon\u2019s final ever senior league match was in a Roope Rooster semi final loss to his old City Rovers team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/City Defeat Devonport\n| page = 14\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII\n| date = 1925-08-17\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250817.2.136\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926, 27, 28, and again in 1934 Haddon played in several veteran player exhibition matches. On October 30, 1926 Haddon made an appearance in an end of season game played between well known league veterans at Carlaw Park. Haddon was representing early New Zealand rugby league legends [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = End of Season Games/Veteran Players in Action\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19473\n| date = 1926-11-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19261101.2.138\n| accessdate = 2020-04-14}}</ref>. The match finished 10-10 and featured the likes of [[Eric Bennett (New Zealand)|Eric Bennett]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], and [[Thomas McClymont]]. In September, 1927 he was chosen in a Devonport United veteran team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby League/Devonport United\n| page = 11\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 207\n| date = 1927-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19270902.2.138.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. Then again in October he played for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team against \u201cShaver\u201d Hargreaves team. The match featured [[Ernie Asher]], [[Jim Rukutai]], [[Thomas McClymont]], [[Dougie McGregor]], [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|Billy Wynyard]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], and [[Bert Laing]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Relief of Unemployed\n| page = 10\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LVIII, Issue 248\n| date = 1927-10-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19271020.2.150\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>. He played in another match in 1928 between City and Ponsonby and then again in 1934 once again for [[Albert Asher]]\u2019s team <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, 24 September\n| date = 1928-09-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19280924.2.148.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Charity Day\n| page = 15\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXV, Issue 244\n| date = 1934-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19341015.2.153\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n===Mt Albert Selector===\nIn 1935 and 36 Tom Haddon was elected as a selector for the [[Mt Albert Lions|Mt Albert]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Mt Albert United Club\n| page = 16\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 53\n| date = 1936-03-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360303.2.193\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/The Coming Season\n| page = 14\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXVII, Issue 87\n| date = 1936-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19360413.2.149\n| accessdate = 2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haddon, Tom}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:City Rovers players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Haddon"}
{"title_page": "Charlie McDonnell", "text_new": "{{short description|British vlogger}}\n{{other people5|Charlie McDonnell (footballer)|Charlie MacDonell}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charlie McDonnell\n| image              = Charlie McDonnell by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image_size         = 220px\n| alt                = \n| caption            = McDonnell at [[VidCon]] in 2014\n| birth_name         = Charles Joseph McDonnell\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1990|10|01}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[England]], UK\n| partner            = Emily Diana Ruth\n| years_active       = 2007\u20132018\n| known_for          = [[Video blogging|Vlogging]], [[filmmaking]], music\n| website            = {{url|charliemcdonnell.com}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox YouTube personality|embed = yes\n| channel_name = charlieissocoollike\n| location = \n| channel_website = \n| creator = \n| presenter = \n| years_active = \n| genre = \n| subscribers = 2.2 million\n| subscriber_date = April 2019\n| views = 298.2 million\n| view_date = April 2019\n| network = \n| associated_acts = \n| catchphrase(s) = \n| silver_button = yes\n| silver_year = 2011\n| gold_button = yes\n| gold_year = 2011\n| diamond_button = \n| diamond_year = \n| ruby_button = \n| ruby_year = \n| module = \n| module_personal = \n| stats_update = 4 April 2019\n| extra_information = \n}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Joseph McDonnell''' (born 1 October 1990) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[vlogger]], musician, [[filmmaker]], and author from [[Bath, Somerset]].<ref name=\"BBC\" /> On 15 June 2011, his [[YouTube]] channel ''charlieissocoollike'' became the first in the [[UK]] to reach one million subscribers, and in May 2013, his channel reached two million subscribers. As a musician, McDonnell was a member of ''[[Doctor Who]]''-themed rock band [[Chameleon Circuit (band)|Chameleon Circuit]] and was also a member of the short-lived project [[Sons of Admirals]] until it was disbanded in May 2011. In 2010, McDonnell released a solo album titled ''This Is Me''. McDonnell directed a series of short films from 2013 to 2014, and co-hosted the weekday morning [[YouTube]] [[breakfast show]] ''[[Cereal Time]]'' with [[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]] presenter and fellow YouTube vlogger [[Jimmy Hill (broadcaster)|Jimmy Hill]] from 2015 to 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCOGelyFJnrzeNWh0y5JfZOQ |title=Cereal Time |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2016-09-20 |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2016, he published his first book, ''Fun Science''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/youtubers-fun-science-debut-quadrille-323795|title=YouTuber's 'Fun Science' debut to Quadrille {{!}} The Bookseller|website=www.thebookseller.com|access-date=2016-10-24}}</ref> After transitioning from personal blog to the 'Fun Science' format, McDonnell stopped uploading new content on his YouTube channel and has removed all content from his website since December 2018.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nMcDonnell was born and raised in [[Bath, Somerset]] to parents Lindsey and Mark.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |title= Teenager's tea tips cause a stir |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/7022544.stm |publisher=BBC  |date=1 October 2007 |accessdate=7 November 2007 }}</ref> He has two younger siblings: his brother, William, and his sister, Bridie. He was educated at [[Beechen Cliff School]],<ref>[http://www.thisisbath.co.uk/news/Charlie-s-good/article-368021-detail/article.html Charlie McDonnell profile]. Thisisbath.co.uk (1 October 2008). Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref> a state comprehensive [[foundation school]] in Bath. He identifies as an [[atheist]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=Hotness Points|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l4yy94mJnC0|work=YouTube|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=28 September 2010}}</ref> McDonnell used to live with fellow video blogger [[Alex Day]], but later lived in his own apartment in [[London]] with his girlfriend. In June 2017, he moved to [[Canada]] (his girlfriend's homeland), where he currently resides.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McDonnell|first1=Charlie|title=So\u2026 I know you'll think I'm joking when I say \"I'm moving to Canada!\" given the current state of the UK. But I'm actually moving to Canada.|url=https://twitter.com/coollike/status/873243836566384640|author2=@coollike|website=Twitter.com|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, McDonnell made a video announcing his relationship with then-girlfriend, fellow YouTuber, Bryarly Bishop.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=My Public Relationship|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RDZ4NCzxRPs|work=YouTube|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> They broke up in June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=My (Slightly Less) Public Breakup|url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/my-public-breakup/|work=charliemcdonnell.com|publisher=Charlie McDonnell|accessdate=16 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515085604/http://charliemcdonnell.com/my-public-breakup/|archive-date=15 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Charlie's current girlfriend is Emily Diana Ruth, a fellow YouTuber and filmmaker.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=The Inevitability of Change (I Moved Out)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CHelQpOFueA|work=YouTube|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=Impromptu trip to Brighton with Emily means obnoxiously cute selfie. Sorry not sorry.|url=https://twitter.com/coollike/status/462594565200154624|website=Twitter.com|publisher=Charlie McDonnell|accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, McDonnell announced on his blog that he has terminated his friendship and cohabitation with Alex Day, stating that \"I just don\u2019t feel able to call Alex a friend of mine anymore\", following allegations that Alex sexually manipulated, emotionally abused, and cheated on past girlfriends.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/sexual-abuse-consent-and-losing-friends/ |title=\"Sexual Abuse, Consent, and Losing Friends\" - charliemcdonnell.com |access-date=8 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408223115/http://charliemcdonnell.com/sexual-abuse-consent-and-losing-friends/ |archive-date=8 April 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Butterly|first=Amelia|title=Vlogger admits 'manipulative relationships with women'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/26664725|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC Newsbeat|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==YouTube==\nAfter setting up the YouTube channel, ''charlieissocoollike'' on 3 April 2007, McDonnell started posting [[video blog]]s (or ''vlogs'') to a small audience. He first came to prominence when his video titled ''How To Get Featured on YouTube'' became popular after it was featured on YouTube's UK homepage. His audience jumped from just under 150 subscribers to over 4,000 in two days.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WrVPzmtGD80 The day in a life of series: Charlie is so cool like]</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, in celebration of gaining 25,000 subscribers, McDonnell asked for challenge suggestions from subscribers, and he is completing them in a series of 25 videos titled ''Challenge Charlie''. He has completed all of these challenges {{as of|2013|03|lc=on}}, one of which was suggested by TV presenter, [[Phillip Schofield]], and his daughter Molly, challenging McDonnell to perform the dance that accompanies the song, [[Hoedown Throwdown]], made popular in the film [[Hannah Montana: The Movie]]. McDonnell has since posted a wide range of videos on the site including his most viewed ''My American Accent''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1564707/Schoolboy%27s-%27how-to-be-English%27-guide-a-US-hit.html|title=Schoolboy's 'how to be English' guide a US hit|last=Paris|first=Natalie|date=2 October 2007|work=Telegraph|accessdate=24 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, McDonnell participated in a video-blog collaboration with four other YouTube personalities, titled ''FiveAwesomeGuys'', a spin-off project of the ''FiveAwesomeGirls'' which featured ''hayleyghoover'' and ''italktosnakes'' and ran from 28 January to 31 December of that year. In May 2009, McDonnell created an alternate YouTube account, ''CharlieAtE3'', which followed McDonnell when he traveled to [[E3 2009]]. In January 2010 McDonnell created another alternate YouTube channel, ''charlieissoboredlike'', for the videos he makes when he has nothing better to do.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/charlieissoboredlike Kanaal van charlieissoboredlike]. YouTube (25 January 2010). Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, McDonnell became the first YouTuber in the United Kingdom to ever reach 1 million subscribers. McDonnell's videos currently end with an [[epilogue|outro]] by [[Stephen Fry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WIussgh00j8|title=Comic Con Vloggin'|last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |publisher=YouTube|date=24 July 2009|accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref> now also inclusive with a ''quali-tea'' stamp.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PWWRD-tkvSg|title=This Week In...|last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |publisher=YouTube|date=1 June 2012|accessdate=23 January 2013}}</ref> In May 2013, McDonnell hit two million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/coollike/status/330586460757561345 |title=Twitter / @coollike: Thanks to everyone who wished ...|website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2013, McDonnell announced that he would be making five short films, in preparation for the feature film that he is currently writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5DPlCUd_0BQ |title=I'm Excited |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=8 March 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> In a video published on 27 October 2014, he announced his last two films would actually be one film, split into two parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1BlZsPmsxmo |title=Thank You :) |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=27 October 2014 |accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> On 6 March 2019, McDonnell announced on Twitter he was quitting YouTube to pursue screenwriting instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/coollike/status/1103386837018656768?s=19 |title=Twitter / @coollike|website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n\n===Short films===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Release date\n! scope=\"col\" | Writer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Producer\n! scope=\"col\" | Genre\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''The Tea Chronicles''\n| {{Start date|df=yes|2013|5|23}}\n| Charlie McDonnell and Khyan Mansley\n| Matt Diegan\n| [[Psychological horror]] [[Comedy film|comedy]]\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pvscHJIkZ84 |title=The Tea Chronicles - Trailer |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=10 May 2013 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |access-date=11 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TtsXLxwuCIg |title=The Tea Chronicles |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=23 May 2013 |publisher=YouTube |access-date=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Offline''\n| {{Start date|df=yes|2013|12|14}}\n| Alan Flanagan and Charlie McDonnell\n| Emily Diana Ruth\n| [[Disaster film|Disaster]] comedy\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EZ2nS6I1k30 |title=OFFLINE - Trailer |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=15 November 2013 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |access-date=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VhZFYY8qT9M |title=OFFLINE - Full Film |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=14 December 2013 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |access-date=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Strangers in a Bed''\n| {{Start date|df=yes|2014|6|28}}\n| Michael Aranda and Charlie McDonnell\n| Emily Diana Ruth\n| Western drama \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/the-super-official-charlie-at-vidcon-2014-schedule/ |title=The *Super Official* Charlie At VidCon 2014 Schedule |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=22 June 2014 |publisher=Charlie McDonnell |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625093735/http://charliemcdonnell.com/the-super-official-charlie-at-vidcon-2014-schedule/ |archive-date=25 June 2014 |access-date=26 June 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Our Brother ''\n| {{Start and end dates|df=yes|2014|10|29|2014|10|30}}\n| Charlie McDonnell\n| Emily Diana Ruth\n| Drama \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vu8KUfs_PTY |title=Our Brother - Part One |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=29 October 2014 |publisher=Charlie McDonnell |access-date=30 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RkRNnrzjz74 |title=Our Brother - Part Two |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=29 October 2014 |publisher=Charlie McDonnell |access-date=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Musical history==\n\n===Chameleon Circuit===\n{{Main|Chameleon Circuit (band)}}\n\n[[File:ChamCirc VidCon 2011 4.jpg|thumb|McDonnell performing with Chameleon Circuit at [[VidCon]] 2011.]]\nMcDonnell is one of the founding members of Chameleon Circuit, a band known for creating music inspired by the British television series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. Along with fellow vloggers [[Alex Day]] (''Nerimon'' on YouTube), Liam Dryden (''Littleradge''), and former member Chris Beattie (''CowInParachute''), Chameleon Circuit released their self-titled debut album on 1 June 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title=Music \u2013 Chameleon Circuit \u2013 DFTBA Records LLC |url=http://dftba.com/shop/categories/Music/Chameleon-Circuit/ |publisher=DFTBA records |accessdate=7 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403201219/http://dftba.com/shop/categories/Music/Chameleon-Circuit |archivedate=3 April 2010  }}</ref> In July 2010, their song ''Count the Shadows'' also appeared on ''DFTBA Records, Volume Two'', a compilation sampler that was given for free in the grab bags at [[VidCon]] 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=Available for FREE, exclusively at VidCon |url=http://dailybooth.com/alandistro/4981569 |accessdate=14 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523220934/http://dailybooth.com/alandistro/4981569 |archivedate=23 May 2010  }}</ref> At the beginning of 2011, Chameleon Circuit, in their new line-up following the departure of Beattie and the addition of Ed Blann (''Eddplant'') and [[Michael aranda|Michael Aranda]], began work on their second album ''[[Still Got Legs]]''. It was released on 12 July 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Music \u2013 Chameleon Circuit \u2013 DFTBA Records LLC |url=http://dftba.com/shop/categories/Music/Chameleon-Circuit/ |publisher=DFTBA records |accessdate=15 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403201219/http://dftba.com/shop/categories/Music/Chameleon-Circuit |archivedate=3 April 2010  }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, Chameleon Circuit have been on an apparent indefinite hiatus, after both McDonnell and Dryden publicly denounced members Blann and Day, who have both suspended their online careers following separate reported incidents of sexual abuse.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sexual Abuse, Consent, and Losing Friends |url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/sexual-abuse-consent-and-losing-friends/ |publisher=Charlie McDonnell |accessdate=13 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720150138/http://charliemcdonnell.com/sexual-abuse-consent-and-losing-friends/ |archive-date=20 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Liam Dryden \u2022 On This Week. |url=http://liamdryden.tumblr.com/post/79554089056/on-this-week |accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> McDonnell, Dryden and Aranda appeared together at VidCon 2014 for photo signings.<ref>{{cite web |title=Signings - VidCon 2014 |url=http://vidcon.com/signings |publisher=VidCon 2014 |accessdate=13 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714203143/http://vidcon.com/signings |archivedate=14 July 2014  }}</ref>\n\n===Sons of Admirals===\nIn 2010, McDonnell, along with three other YouTubers, [[Alex Day]] (\"nerimon\"), Ed Blann (\"eddplant\") and Tom Milsom (\"Hexachordal\") formed a new project titled \"Sons of Admirals\". Their first single was released via YouTube on 14 June 2010 on McDonnell's channel. The group covered [[Cat Stevens|Cat Steven]]s' song \"[[Here Comes My Baby (Cat Stevens song)|Here Comes My Baby]]\" featuring all four members on vocals. The track peaked at No.&nbsp;61 in the UK.<ref>[http://www.polyhex.com polyhex]. polyhex. Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref> <br>In October 2010 the band released an EP including \"Here Comes My Baby\"; an acoustic version of the same song; a cover of \"Believe in Yourself\", the theme of children's television show ''[[Arthur (TV series)|Arthur]]''; the music video of \"Here Comes My Baby\"; and a behind-the-scenes video. The band has been known to perform a cover of \"You're Not There\", written by Ed Blann, and a cover of [[Radiohead]]'s \"[[Creep (Radiohead song)|Creep]]\".<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/here-comes-my-baby-ep/id399010503 iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Here Comes My Baby \u2013 EP by Sons of Admirals]. Itunes.apple.com (25 October 2010). Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref>\n\nSons of Admirals was not a band in the traditional sense. They were all solo artists, but as well as having their solo careers, they came together to form one group. The idea and name inspiration for this came from the [[Admiral's Men]], which was a [[Shakespeare]]an group of actors that came together to perform, while still retaining their individual careers.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=slIyXbXYX4o Sons of Admirals on The 5:19 Show!]. YouTube. Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref>\n\nSons of Admirals disbanded in May 2011, publishing a statement on their website that \"the core goal of the group \u2013 to get into the charts, and to increase exposure for the group members' individual talents proved to run against too many of our beliefs and approaches to music and promotion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonsofadmirals.com/|title=Sons of Admirals Website|accessdate=24 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716104406/http://sonsofadmirals.com/|archive-date=16 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Solo career===\n\nA prominent feature of McDonnell's YouTube channel are the songs which he writes and performs himself, usually on a ukulele, but also featuring other instruments such as the guitar, melodica, and\u2014in one song\u2014a kazoo and a xylophone made of filled water glasses.  The most popular of these is \"Duet with Myself.\"  On 1 December 2010, in response to many fan requests to do so, he released his debut album titled ''This is Me'' via [[DFTBA Records]].  The album features several songs from his channel that was remixed for the album, as well as several new, previously unreleased songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=This is Me (CD)|url=http://dftba.com/product/wz/This-Is-Me-CD|access-date=5 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007004354/http://dftba.com/product/wz/This-Is-Me-CD|archive-date=7 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2012 McDonnell posted a video of him singing an original song ''Time To Reply'' on his YouTube channel, which received highly positive feedback.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nIn 2014, McDonnell's YouTube Channel, charlieissocoollike, was listed on [[New Media Rockstars]] Top 100 Channels, ranked at #63.<ref>{{cite web|title=The NMR Top 100 YouTube Channels: 75-51!|url= http://newmediarockstars.com/2014/12/the-nmr-top-100-youtube-channels-75-51/|website=New Media Rockstars|accessdate=6 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Music videos===\n* \"Here Comes My Baby\" (2010)\n* [[Forever Yours (Alex Day song)|\"Forever Yours\"]] (2011)\n\n[[Alex Day]] (a.k.a. [[nerimon]]), has released a number of tracks on YouTube as music videos, such as the highly popular [[Forever Yours (Alex Day song)|Forever Yours]], which peaked at number 4 in the UK charts. The music videos for a number of these were directed by McDonnell, some even starring him or featuring him at some point in the video.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n==Charity and media work==\nOn 30 September 2008, to celebrate his 18th birthday, McDonnell and Alex Day dyed and then shaved their hair off whilst live on [[BlogTV]] for a period of seven and a half hours in aid of [[Cancer Research UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisbath.co.uk/news/winnersarticle-579579-details/article.html |title=The Bath Chronicle |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=22 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804085850/http://www.thisisbath.co.uk/news/winnersarticle-579579-details/article.html |archivedate=4 August 2009 }}</ref> They managed to raise nearly \u00a35000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://justgiving.com/blogtvbirthday|title=Just Giving|accessdate=22 April 2009}}</ref> The broadcast viewership peaked at 4,500. Another friend, Jazza John (known as ''rhymingwithoranges'' on YouTube) promised to shave his head if they hit \u00a34000 and did so about a month later with help from Kristina Horner (known as ''italktosnakes'' and ''Monday'' on the YouTube collab-channel ''fiveawesomegirls'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ws_7VYGoIjQ |title=11/10: Kristina is dangerous with a shaver. |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2008-11-10 |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, McDonnell was named as one of a number of prominent YouTube users who would be participating in a project called ''RNLI Shout''.  The aim of the project is to raise money to purchase a lifeboat for the [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution]].\n\nOn 4 September 2010, McDonnell and fellow YouTuber Myles Dyer co-presented Stickaid, a 24-hour live web show. Starting from 12:00 noon [[British Summer Time|BST]], the two hosted the fifth annual charity event from [[Middlesex University|Middlesex University's]] Trent Park campus in London. Their goal was to raise \u00a310,000 ($15,900), which they more than doubled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justgiving.com/stickaid2010/|title=Just Giving|accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref> All the proceedings went to [[UNICEF]].\n\n===The Science of Attraction===\nIn November 2010, McDonnell was part of a group of YouTube videos called ''The Science of Attraction'' where he hosted a few experiments and had his body digitally swapped with somebody else's. He was a co-presenter with Kat Akingbade and Derren Brown. As part of the series, eight videos were produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yosfPU3dWgc |title=Familiar Faces - Science of Attraction |author=Science of Attraction |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Chartjackers===\n{{main|Chartjackers}}\nIn the autumn of 2009, McDonnell featured with three other YouTube users on the [[BBC Switch]] documentary series ''[[Chartjackers]]''. The programme documented their attempt to achieve a number one single in the [[UK Singles Chart]] within 10 weeks, by [[crowdsourcing]] resources provided by the [[online community]]. McDonnell was cast in the series for his familiarity to young British YouTube viewers and to act as a [[Pied Piper]] to the teen audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/commissioning/tv/network/genres/entertainment_detail.shtml|title=Entertainment Development Priorities|publisher=BBC  |location=London|accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of ''Chartjackers'', McDonnell solicited lyrics, music, performers and stylists to record the final single and video via a YouTube channel named ''ChartJackersProject''. An unofficial [[charity single]] for [[Children in Need]], the completed song was titled [[I've Got Nothing]] and was sung by vocalists [[Miranda Chartrand and Adam Nichols]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Episode 6|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zFoBwlOv-70|series=Chartjackers|network=[[BBC]]|station=BBC Two |location=UK|airdate=17 October 2009|seriesno=1|number=6}}</ref> McDonnell edited the single's official music video,<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Episode 7|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=baXD5a4-yHg|series=Chartjackers|network=[[BBC]]|station=BBC Two |location=UK|airdate=24 October 2009|seriesno=1|number=7}}</ref> which was shown nationwide on British [[Music television|music channels]] such as [[4Music]] and [[Viva (UK & Ireland)|Viva]]. ''I've Got Nothing'' was released exclusively through the [[iTunes Store]] at midnight on 9 November 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pudsey/news/news061109b.shtml|title=Chartjackers attack the charts|date=November 2009|publisher=BBC  |location=London|accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref> and reached No.&nbsp;36 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singles Chart For 21 November 2009|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=16 November 2009|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/|accessdate=16 December 2009}}</ref> Sales of the single raised a total of approximately \u00a310,000 for Children in Need.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Compilation|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R5csWCO5STI|series=Chartjackers|credits=Producers: Jonathan Davenport and Adam King|network=[[BBC]]|station=BBC Two |location=UK|airdate=21 November 2009|seriesno=1|number=11}}</ref>\n\n===''FirstTV''===\nIn July 2010 McDonnell was signed up alongside ''[[KateModern]]'' star Emma Pollard and ''[[The X Factor (UK)|X Factor]]'' contestants Nicola and Fran Gleadall to present a TV show run by [[Piers Morgan]] called ''FirstTV'', an offshoot of ''[[First News]]'' newspaper. On First TV he did a few challenges like trying to break a [[Guinness world record]] by [[typing]] the [[alphabet]] on an [[iPad]] [[Keyboard (computing)|keyboard]] quickest and he got asked to tell a [[joke]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nma.co.uk/news/piers-morgan-to-launch-first-tv-on-web/3015826.article|title=Piers Morgan to launch First TV on web|last=Davies|first=Jessica|date=14 July 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607155455/http://www.nma.co.uk/news/piers-morgan-to-launch-first-tv-on-web/3015826.article|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstnews.co.uk/news/firsttv-is-here-i1936|title=FirstTV is here!|date=9 July 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010|newspaper=[[First News]]}}</ref> However, after filming four episodes of ''FirstTV'', McDonnell decided to leave the show because he did not enjoy presenting pre-scripted work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/vidcon-firsttv/|title=VidCon & FirstTV|publisher=CharlieMcDonnell.com|date=16 July 2010|accessdate=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120713193109/http://charliemcdonnell.com/vidcon-firsttv/|archive-date=13 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===''Volume''===\nIn October 2013, it was announced that McDonnell was to play the main voice role along with [[BAFTA Awards|BAFTA Award]]-winning [[Danny Wallace (humourist)|Danny Wallace]] in [[Mike Bithell]]'s indie video game ''[[Volume (video game)|Volume]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1qNQJEQjks8 |title=Volume - Actor Announcement |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2013-10-25 |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> The game was released in 2015 for [[PS4]], [[Personal computer|PC game]] and [[Macintosh|Mac]] and in 2016 for [[PlayStation Vita]].\n\n===This Is Abuse===\nIn 2014, McDonnell worked with the [[Home Office]] on their ''This Is Abuse'' Campaign, alongside other prominent YouTubers, in order to educate people about the importance of consensual sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/26545056|title=YouTube vloggers star in new abuse campaign|publisher=BBC  |location=London|accessdate=8 April 2014|date=13 March 2014}}</ref> He also made a video regarding consent on his YouTube channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3GVfesRwvsQ |title=Sex & Consent |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2014-03-20 |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> This campaign by the Home Office came following public discovery of allegiations of sexually abusive behavior committed by British YouTuber Alex Day (an ex-friend/collaborator of McDonnell).{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Production companies==\nIn June 2011, McDonnell founded ''Coollike Productions'' which would become his base for the production of short films and his YouTube channel, according to the online business website [[Duedil]], McDonnell is the company's only director and in May 2013 the company was renamed as ''Qualitea Productions''. It is based in Central London. Reports circulated that a high-level production company wanted to buy the company last year, however, these reports have since been quashed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.duedil.com/company/gb/07685161/qualitea-productions-limited/directors |website=www.duedil.com/|title= Qualitea Productions Limited|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Press==\nMcDonnell was interviewed on [[BBC News]] about his rise to internet stardom. He also participated in the Euro 2008 Zeitgeist [[Google]] conference, where he spoke about YouTube along with [[Mia Rose]] (''miaarose'') and [[Peter Oakley]] (''geriatric1927''). This was a conference to honour online users of popular websites. He featured as a guest on [[Robert Llewellyn]]'s web series ''[[Carpool (web series)|Carpool]]'' in the episode released on 15 May 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebritytweet.com/bobbyllew/link/1361381818/|title=Robert Llewellyn @bobbyllew |quote=This weekend I am shooting a carpool with ''charlieissocoollike''.|publisher=CelebrityTweet!|date=8 February 2018 }}</ref> McDonnell has also made guest appearances on ''[[Lily Allen and Friends]]'' and ''[[The Gadget Show]]''.\n\nMcDonnell was also interviewed for Outlook on the [[BBC World Service]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/programmes/2010/04/100428_outlook_charlie_mcdonnell.shtml|title=The YouTubing teenager getting four million hits a month|quote=Charlie has used the website to broadcast his homemade videos and currently gets an amazing four million hits a month.|publisher=BBC }}</ref> and for an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'' where he talks about the five years of YouTube and his life on the video website.\n\nOn 6 June 2010, McDonnell presented the YouTube Audience Award to [[The Inbetweeners]] as part of the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] Television Awards. In mid-July 2010, McDonnell appeared on KTLA with [[Hank Green]], known on YouTube as one of the [[Vlogbrothers]], and [[iJustine]] to promote VidCon 2010, the first international conference for online video makers. That October he made a programme with [[James Max]] of [[LBC 97.3]] about how to make money on the internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lbc.audioagain.com/index.php?sid=1&player=showchannel&channel_id=349|title=James Max speaks to Charlie McDonnell \u2013 3 Oct 10|quote=Listen back to the Business Hour with James Max as he was joined by the most popular YouTuber in the UK \u2013 Charlie McDonnell, AKA Charlie Is So Cool Like.|publisher=LBC Podcasts}}</ref> In December 2010, McDonnell filmed a series of behind the scenes videos for ''[[Doctor Who Confidential]]'' during the filming of the ''Doctor Who'' Christmas special [[A Christmas Carol (Doctor Who)|A Christmas Carol]].\n\nMcDonnell was purportedly approached to be a Housemate on the eighth series, and first revived series of ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (UK TV series)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' but declined the offer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/coollike/status/104287671916044289|title=Twitter / @coollike: I would like to...|website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n\nAstronomer [[Phil Plait]] wrote an article for Slate.com (\"Charlie Talks Saturn,\" 8 December 2012) to rave about McDonnell's ongoing series of science videos, including \"Fun Science: Saturn,\" on which Plait gave him some assistance.  Plait found McDonnell to be a \"science nerd\" and a \"really nice guy\" who makes \"engaging, silly and fun\" videos that reach lots of young people who \"need to find their own love of science.\"\n\nA 13 February 2013, New York Times article, \"Blogging with Video, Hoping to Go Viral,\" noted that McDonnell, described as \"a musician and professed nerd with soulful eyes\", has 1.8 million subscribers to [his] video blog or vlog.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm3726055}}\n\n{{Chartjackers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonnell, Charlie}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Chartjackers]]\n[[Category:DFTBA Records creators]]\n[[Category:English atheists]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:English video bloggers]]\n[[Category:English YouTubers]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:People educated at Beechen Cliff School]]\n[[Category:People from Bath, Somerset]]\n[[Category:People from Somerset]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British vlogger}}\n{{other people5|Charlie McDonnell (footballer)|Charlie MacDonell}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charlie McDonnell\n| image              = Charlie McDonnell by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image_size         = 220px\n| alt                = \n| caption            = McDonnell at [[VidCon]] in 2014\n| birth_name         = Charles Joseph McDonnell\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1990|10|01}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[England]], UK\n| partner            = Emily Diana Ruth\n| years_active       = 2007\u20132018\n| known_for          = [[Video blogging|Vlogging]], [[filmmaking]], music\n| website            = {{url|charliemcdonnell.com}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox YouTube personality|embed = yes\n| channel_name = charlieissocoollike\n| location = \n| channel_website = \n| creator = \n| presenter = \n| years_active = \n| genre = \n| subscribers = 2.2 million\n| subscriber_date = April 2019\n| views = 298.2 million\n| view_date = April 2019\n| network = \n| associated_acts = \n| catchphrase(s) = \n| silver_button = yes\n| silver_year = 2011\n| gold_button = yes\n| gold_year = 2011\n| diamond_button = \n| diamond_year = \n| ruby_button = \n| ruby_year = \n| module = \n| module_personal = \n| stats_update = 4 April 2019\n| extra_information = \n}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Joseph McDonnell''' (born 1 October 1990) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[vlogger]], musician, [[filmmaker]], and author from [[Bath, Somerset]].<ref name=\"BBC\" /> On 15 June 2011, his [[YouTube]] channel ''charlieissocoollike'' became the first in the [[UK]] to reach one million subscribers, and in May 2013, his channel reached two million subscribers. As a musician, McDonnell was a member of ''[[Doctor Who]]''-themed rock band [[Chameleon Circuit (band)|Chameleon Circuit]] and was also a member of the short-lived project [[Sons of Admirals]] until it was disbanded in May 2011. In 2010, McDonnell released a solo album titled ''This Is Me''. McDonnell directed a series of short films from 2013 to 2014, and co-hosted the weekday morning [[YouTube]] [[breakfast show]] ''[[Cereal Time]]'' with [[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]] presenter and fellow YouTube vlogger [[Jimmy Hill (broadcaster)|Jimmy Hill]] from 2015 to 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCOGelyFJnrzeNWh0y5JfZOQ |title=Cereal Time |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2016-09-20 |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2016, he published his first book, ''Fun Science''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/youtubers-fun-science-debut-quadrille-323795|title=YouTuber's 'Fun Science' debut to Quadrille {{!}} The Bookseller|website=www.thebookseller.com|access-date=2016-10-24}}</ref> After transitioning from personal blog to the 'Fun Science' format, McDonnell stopped uploading new content on his YouTube channel and has removed all content from his website since December 2018.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nMcDonnell was born and raised in [[Bath, Somerset]] to parents Lindsey and Mark.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news |title= Teenager's tea tips cause a stir |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/7022544.stm |publisher=BBC  |date=1 October 2007 |accessdate=7 November 2007 }}</ref> He has two younger siblings: his brother, William, and his sister, Bridie. He was educated at [[Beechen Cliff School]],<ref>[http://www.thisisbath.co.uk/news/Charlie-s-good/article-368021-detail/article.html Charlie McDonnell profile]. Thisisbath.co.uk (1 October 2008). Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref> a state comprehensive [[foundation school]] in Bath. He identifies as an [[atheist]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=Hotness Points|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l4yy94mJnC0|work=YouTube|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=28 September 2010}}</ref> McDonnell used to live with fellow video blogger [[Alex Day]], but later lived in his own apartment in [[London]] with his girlfriend. In June 2017, he moved to [[Canada]] (his girlfriend's homeland), where he currently resides.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McDonnell|first1=Charlie|title=So\u2026 I know you'll think I'm joking when I say \"I'm moving to Canada!\" given the current state of the UK. But I'm actually moving to Canada.|url=https://twitter.com/coollike/status/873243836566384640|author=@coollike|website=Twitter.com|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, McDonnell made a video announcing his relationship with then-girlfriend, fellow YouTuber, Bryarly Bishop.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=My Public Relationship|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RDZ4NCzxRPs|work=YouTube|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> They broke up in June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=My (Slightly Less) Public Breakup|url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/my-public-breakup/|work=charliemcdonnell.com|publisher=Charlie McDonnell|accessdate=16 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515085604/http://charliemcdonnell.com/my-public-breakup/|archive-date=15 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Charlie's current girlfriend is Emily Diana Ruth, a fellow YouTuber and filmmaker.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=The Inevitability of Change (I Moved Out)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CHelQpOFueA|work=YouTube|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=Charlie|title=Impromptu trip to Brighton with Emily means obnoxiously cute selfie. Sorry not sorry.|url=https://twitter.com/coollike/status/462594565200154624|website=Twitter.com|publisher=Charlie McDonnell|accessdate=16 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, McDonnell announced on his blog that he has terminated his friendship and cohabitation with Alex Day, stating that \"I just don\u2019t feel able to call Alex a friend of mine anymore\", following allegations that Alex sexually manipulated, emotionally abused, and cheated on past girlfriends.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/sexual-abuse-consent-and-losing-friends/ |title=\"Sexual Abuse, Consent, and Losing Friends\" - charliemcdonnell.com |access-date=8 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408223115/http://charliemcdonnell.com/sexual-abuse-consent-and-losing-friends/ |archive-date=8 April 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Butterly|first=Amelia|title=Vlogger admits 'manipulative relationships with women'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/26664725|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC Newsbeat|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==YouTube==\nAfter setting up the YouTube channel, ''charlieissocoollike'' on 3 April 2007, McDonnell started posting [[video blog]]s (or ''vlogs'') to a small audience. He first came to prominence when his video titled ''How To Get Featured on YouTube'' became popular after it was featured on YouTube's UK homepage. His audience jumped from just under 150 subscribers to over 4,000 in two days.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WrVPzmtGD80 The day in a life of series: Charlie is so cool like]</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, in celebration of gaining 25,000 subscribers, McDonnell asked for challenge suggestions from subscribers, and he is completing them in a series of 25 videos titled ''Challenge Charlie''. He has completed all of these challenges {{as of|2013|03|lc=on}}, one of which was suggested by TV presenter, [[Phillip Schofield]], and his daughter Molly, challenging McDonnell to perform the dance that accompanies the song, [[Hoedown Throwdown]], made popular in the film [[Hannah Montana: The Movie]]. McDonnell has since posted a wide range of videos on the site including his most viewed ''My American Accent''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1564707/Schoolboy%27s-%27how-to-be-English%27-guide-a-US-hit.html|title=Schoolboy's 'how to be English' guide a US hit|last=Paris|first=Natalie|date=2 October 2007|work=Telegraph|accessdate=24 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, McDonnell participated in a video-blog collaboration with four other YouTube personalities, titled ''FiveAwesomeGuys'', a spin-off project of the ''FiveAwesomeGirls'' which featured ''hayleyghoover'' and ''italktosnakes'' and ran from 28 January to 31 December of that year. In May 2009, McDonnell created an alternate YouTube account, ''CharlieAtE3'', which followed McDonnell when he traveled to [[E3 2009]]. In January 2010 McDonnell created another alternate YouTube channel, ''charlieissoboredlike'', for the videos he makes when he has nothing better to do.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/charlieissoboredlike Kanaal van charlieissoboredlike]. YouTube (25 January 2010). Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, McDonnell became the first YouTuber in the United Kingdom to ever reach 1 million subscribers. McDonnell's videos currently end with an [[epilogue|outro]] by [[Stephen Fry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WIussgh00j8|title=Comic Con Vloggin'|last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |publisher=YouTube|date=24 July 2009|accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref> now also inclusive with a ''quali-tea'' stamp.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PWWRD-tkvSg|title=This Week In...|last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |publisher=YouTube|date=1 June 2012|accessdate=23 January 2013}}</ref> In May 2013, McDonnell hit two million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/coollike/status/330586460757561345 |title=Twitter / @coollike: Thanks to everyone who wished ...|website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2013, McDonnell announced that he would be making five short films, in preparation for the feature film that he is currently writing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5DPlCUd_0BQ |title=I'm Excited |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=8 March 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> In a video published on 27 October 2014, he announced his last two films would actually be one film, split into two parts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1BlZsPmsxmo |title=Thank You :) |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=27 October 2014 |accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> On 6 March 2019, McDonnell announced on Twitter he was quitting YouTube to pursue screenwriting instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/coollike/status/1103386837018656768?s=19 |title=Twitter / @coollike|website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n\n===Short films===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Release date\n! scope=\"col\" | Writer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Producer\n! scope=\"col\" | Genre\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''The Tea Chronicles''\n| {{Start date|df=yes|2013|5|23}}\n| Charlie McDonnell and Khyan Mansley\n| Matt Diegan\n| [[Psychological horror]] [[Comedy film|comedy]]\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pvscHJIkZ84 |title=The Tea Chronicles - Trailer |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=10 May 2013 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |access-date=11 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TtsXLxwuCIg |title=The Tea Chronicles |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=23 May 2013 |publisher=YouTube |access-date=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Offline''\n| {{Start date|df=yes|2013|12|14}}\n| Alan Flanagan and Charlie McDonnell\n| Emily Diana Ruth\n| [[Disaster film|Disaster]] comedy\n| align=center|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EZ2nS6I1k30 |title=OFFLINE - Trailer |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=15 November 2013 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |access-date=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VhZFYY8qT9M |title=OFFLINE - Full Film |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=14 December 2013 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |access-date=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Strangers in a Bed''\n| {{Start date|df=yes|2014|6|28}}\n| Michael Aranda and Charlie McDonnell\n| Emily Diana Ruth\n| Western drama \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/the-super-official-charlie-at-vidcon-2014-schedule/ |title=The *Super Official* Charlie At VidCon 2014 Schedule |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=22 June 2014 |publisher=Charlie McDonnell |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625093735/http://charliemcdonnell.com/the-super-official-charlie-at-vidcon-2014-schedule/ |archive-date=25 June 2014 |access-date=26 June 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Our Brother ''\n| {{Start and end dates|df=yes|2014|10|29|2014|10|30}}\n| Charlie McDonnell\n| Emily Diana Ruth\n| Drama \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vu8KUfs_PTY |title=Our Brother - Part One |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=29 October 2014 |publisher=Charlie McDonnell |access-date=30 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RkRNnrzjz74 |title=Our Brother - Part Two |last=McDonnell |first=Charlie |date=29 October 2014 |publisher=Charlie McDonnell |access-date=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Musical history==\n\n===Chameleon Circuit===\n{{Main|Chameleon Circuit (band)}}\n\n[[File:ChamCirc VidCon 2011 4.jpg|thumb|McDonnell performing with Chameleon Circuit at [[VidCon]] 2011.]]\nMcDonnell is one of the founding members of Chameleon Circuit, a band known for creating music inspired by the British television series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. Along with fellow vloggers [[Alex Day]] (''Nerimon'' on YouTube), Liam Dryden (''Littleradge''), and former member Chris Beattie (''CowInParachute''), Chameleon Circuit released their self-titled debut album on 1 June 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title=Music \u2013 Chameleon Circuit \u2013 DFTBA Records LLC |url=http://dftba.com/shop/categories/Music/Chameleon-Circuit/ |publisher=DFTBA records |accessdate=7 November 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403201219/http://dftba.com/shop/categories/Music/Chameleon-Circuit |archivedate=3 April 2010  }}</ref> In July 2010, their song ''Count the Shadows'' also appeared on ''DFTBA Records, Volume Two'', a compilation sampler that was given for free in the grab bags at [[VidCon]] 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=Available for FREE, exclusively at VidCon |url=http://dailybooth.com/alandistro/4981569 |accessdate=14 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523220934/http://dailybooth.com/alandistro/4981569 |archivedate=23 May 2010  }}</ref> At the beginning of 2011, Chameleon Circuit, in their new line-up following the departure of Beattie and the addition of Ed Blann (''Eddplant'') and [[Michael aranda|Michael Aranda]], began work on their second album ''[[Still Got Legs]]''. It was released on 12 July 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Music \u2013 Chameleon Circuit \u2013 DFTBA Records LLC |url=http://dftba.com/shop/categories/Music/Chameleon-Circuit/ |publisher=DFTBA records |accessdate=15 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403201219/http://dftba.com/shop/categories/Music/Chameleon-Circuit |archivedate=3 April 2010  }}</ref>\n\nAs of 2014, Chameleon Circuit have been on an apparent indefinite hiatus, after both McDonnell and Dryden publicly denounced members Blann and Day, who have both suspended their online careers following separate reported incidents of sexual abuse.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sexual Abuse, Consent, and Losing Friends |url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/sexual-abuse-consent-and-losing-friends/ |publisher=Charlie McDonnell |accessdate=13 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720150138/http://charliemcdonnell.com/sexual-abuse-consent-and-losing-friends/ |archive-date=20 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Liam Dryden \u2022 On This Week. |url=http://liamdryden.tumblr.com/post/79554089056/on-this-week |accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> McDonnell, Dryden and Aranda appeared together at VidCon 2014 for photo signings.<ref>{{cite web |title=Signings - VidCon 2014 |url=http://vidcon.com/signings |publisher=VidCon 2014 |accessdate=13 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714203143/http://vidcon.com/signings |archivedate=14 July 2014  }}</ref>\n\n===Sons of Admirals===\nIn 2010, McDonnell, along with three other YouTubers, [[Alex Day]] (\"nerimon\"), Ed Blann (\"eddplant\") and Tom Milsom (\"Hexachordal\") formed a new project titled \"Sons of Admirals\". Their first single was released via YouTube on 14 June 2010 on McDonnell's channel. The group covered [[Cat Stevens|Cat Steven]]s' song \"[[Here Comes My Baby (Cat Stevens song)|Here Comes My Baby]]\" featuring all four members on vocals. The track peaked at No.&nbsp;61 in the UK.<ref>[http://www.polyhex.com polyhex]. polyhex. Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref> <br>In October 2010 the band released an EP including \"Here Comes My Baby\"; an acoustic version of the same song; a cover of \"Believe in Yourself\", the theme of children's television show ''[[Arthur (TV series)|Arthur]]''; the music video of \"Here Comes My Baby\"; and a behind-the-scenes video. The band has been known to perform a cover of \"You're Not There\", written by Ed Blann, and a cover of [[Radiohead]]'s \"[[Creep (Radiohead song)|Creep]]\".<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/here-comes-my-baby-ep/id399010503 iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Here Comes My Baby \u2013 EP by Sons of Admirals]. Itunes.apple.com (25 October 2010). Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref>\n\nSons of Admirals was not a band in the traditional sense. They were all solo artists, but as well as having their solo careers, they came together to form one group. The idea and name inspiration for this came from the [[Admiral's Men]], which was a [[Shakespeare]]an group of actors that came together to perform, while still retaining their individual careers.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=slIyXbXYX4o Sons of Admirals on The 5:19 Show!]. YouTube. Retrieved on 28 December 2011.</ref>\n\nSons of Admirals disbanded in May 2011, publishing a statement on their website that \"the core goal of the group \u2013 to get into the charts, and to increase exposure for the group members' individual talents proved to run against too many of our beliefs and approaches to music and promotion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonsofadmirals.com/|title=Sons of Admirals Website|accessdate=24 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716104406/http://sonsofadmirals.com/|archive-date=16 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Solo career===\n\nA prominent feature of McDonnell's YouTube channel are the songs which he writes and performs himself, usually on a ukulele, but also featuring other instruments such as the guitar, melodica, and\u2014in one song\u2014a kazoo and a xylophone made of filled water glasses.  The most popular of these is \"Duet with Myself.\"  On 1 December 2010, in response to many fan requests to do so, he released his debut album titled ''This is Me'' via [[DFTBA Records]].  The album features several songs from his channel that was remixed for the album, as well as several new, previously unreleased songs.<ref>{{cite web|title=This is Me (CD)|url=http://dftba.com/product/wz/This-Is-Me-CD|access-date=5 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007004354/http://dftba.com/product/wz/This-Is-Me-CD|archive-date=7 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2012 McDonnell posted a video of him singing an original song ''Time To Reply'' on his YouTube channel, which received highly positive feedback.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nIn 2014, McDonnell's YouTube Channel, charlieissocoollike, was listed on [[New Media Rockstars]] Top 100 Channels, ranked at #63.<ref>{{cite web|title=The NMR Top 100 YouTube Channels: 75-51!|url= http://newmediarockstars.com/2014/12/the-nmr-top-100-youtube-channels-75-51/|website=New Media Rockstars|accessdate=6 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Music videos===\n* \"Here Comes My Baby\" (2010)\n* [[Forever Yours (Alex Day song)|\"Forever Yours\"]] (2011)\n\n[[Alex Day]] (a.k.a. [[nerimon]]), has released a number of tracks on YouTube as music videos, such as the highly popular [[Forever Yours (Alex Day song)|Forever Yours]], which peaked at number 4 in the UK charts. The music videos for a number of these were directed by McDonnell, some even starring him or featuring him at some point in the video.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n==Charity and media work==\nOn 30 September 2008, to celebrate his 18th birthday, McDonnell and Alex Day dyed and then shaved their hair off whilst live on [[BlogTV]] for a period of seven and a half hours in aid of [[Cancer Research UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisbath.co.uk/news/winnersarticle-579579-details/article.html |title=The Bath Chronicle |date=1 January 2009 |accessdate=22 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804085850/http://www.thisisbath.co.uk/news/winnersarticle-579579-details/article.html |archivedate=4 August 2009 }}</ref> They managed to raise nearly \u00a35000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://justgiving.com/blogtvbirthday|title=Just Giving|accessdate=22 April 2009}}</ref> The broadcast viewership peaked at 4,500. Another friend, Jazza John (known as ''rhymingwithoranges'' on YouTube) promised to shave his head if they hit \u00a34000 and did so about a month later with help from Kristina Horner (known as ''italktosnakes'' and ''Monday'' on the YouTube collab-channel ''fiveawesomegirls'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ws_7VYGoIjQ |title=11/10: Kristina is dangerous with a shaver. |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2008-11-10 |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, McDonnell was named as one of a number of prominent YouTube users who would be participating in a project called ''RNLI Shout''.  The aim of the project is to raise money to purchase a lifeboat for the [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution]].\n\nOn 4 September 2010, McDonnell and fellow YouTuber Myles Dyer co-presented Stickaid, a 24-hour live web show. Starting from 12:00 noon [[British Summer Time|BST]], the two hosted the fifth annual charity event from [[Middlesex University|Middlesex University's]] Trent Park campus in London. Their goal was to raise \u00a310,000 ($15,900), which they more than doubled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justgiving.com/stickaid2010/|title=Just Giving|accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref> All the proceedings went to [[UNICEF]].\n\n===The Science of Attraction===\nIn November 2010, McDonnell was part of a group of YouTube videos called ''The Science of Attraction'' where he hosted a few experiments and had his body digitally swapped with somebody else's. He was a co-presenter with Kat Akingbade and Derren Brown. As part of the series, eight videos were produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yosfPU3dWgc |title=Familiar Faces - Science of Attraction |author=Science of Attraction |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=4 November 2010 |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Chartjackers===\n{{main|Chartjackers}}\nIn the autumn of 2009, McDonnell featured with three other YouTube users on the [[BBC Switch]] documentary series ''[[Chartjackers]]''. The programme documented their attempt to achieve a number one single in the [[UK Singles Chart]] within 10 weeks, by [[crowdsourcing]] resources provided by the [[online community]]. McDonnell was cast in the series for his familiarity to young British YouTube viewers and to act as a [[Pied Piper]] to the teen audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/commissioning/tv/network/genres/entertainment_detail.shtml|title=Entertainment Development Priorities|publisher=BBC  |location=London|accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of ''Chartjackers'', McDonnell solicited lyrics, music, performers and stylists to record the final single and video via a YouTube channel named ''ChartJackersProject''. An unofficial [[charity single]] for [[Children in Need]], the completed song was titled [[I've Got Nothing]] and was sung by vocalists [[Miranda Chartrand and Adam Nichols]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Episode 6|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zFoBwlOv-70|series=Chartjackers|network=[[BBC]]|station=BBC Two |location=UK|airdate=17 October 2009|seriesno=1|number=6}}</ref> McDonnell edited the single's official music video,<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Episode 7|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=baXD5a4-yHg|series=Chartjackers|network=[[BBC]]|station=BBC Two |location=UK|airdate=24 October 2009|seriesno=1|number=7}}</ref> which was shown nationwide on British [[Music television|music channels]] such as [[4Music]] and [[Viva (UK & Ireland)|Viva]]. ''I've Got Nothing'' was released exclusively through the [[iTunes Store]] at midnight on 9 November 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pudsey/news/news061109b.shtml|title=Chartjackers attack the charts|date=November 2009|publisher=BBC  |location=London|accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref> and reached No.&nbsp;36 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singles Chart For 21 November 2009|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=16 November 2009|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/|accessdate=16 December 2009}}</ref> Sales of the single raised a total of approximately \u00a310,000 for Children in Need.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Compilation|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R5csWCO5STI|series=Chartjackers|credits=Producers: Jonathan Davenport and Adam King|network=[[BBC]]|station=BBC Two |location=UK|airdate=21 November 2009|seriesno=1|number=11}}</ref>\n\n===''FirstTV''===\nIn July 2010 McDonnell was signed up alongside ''[[KateModern]]'' star Emma Pollard and ''[[The X Factor (UK)|X Factor]]'' contestants Nicola and Fran Gleadall to present a TV show run by [[Piers Morgan]] called ''FirstTV'', an offshoot of ''[[First News]]'' newspaper. On First TV he did a few challenges like trying to break a [[Guinness world record]] by [[typing]] the [[alphabet]] on an [[iPad]] [[Keyboard (computing)|keyboard]] quickest and he got asked to tell a [[joke]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nma.co.uk/news/piers-morgan-to-launch-first-tv-on-web/3015826.article|title=Piers Morgan to launch First TV on web|last=Davies|first=Jessica|date=14 July 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607155455/http://www.nma.co.uk/news/piers-morgan-to-launch-first-tv-on-web/3015826.article|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstnews.co.uk/news/firsttv-is-here-i1936|title=FirstTV is here!|date=9 July 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010|newspaper=[[First News]]}}</ref> However, after filming four episodes of ''FirstTV'', McDonnell decided to leave the show because he did not enjoy presenting pre-scripted work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://charliemcdonnell.com/vidcon-firsttv/|title=VidCon & FirstTV|publisher=CharlieMcDonnell.com|date=16 July 2010|accessdate=16 July 2010|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120713193109/http://charliemcdonnell.com/vidcon-firsttv/|archive-date=13 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===''Volume''===\nIn October 2013, it was announced that McDonnell was to play the main voice role along with [[BAFTA Awards|BAFTA Award]]-winning [[Danny Wallace (humourist)|Danny Wallace]] in [[Mike Bithell]]'s indie video game ''[[Volume (video game)|Volume]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1qNQJEQjks8 |title=Volume - Actor Announcement |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2013-10-25 |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> The game was released in 2015 for [[PS4]], [[Personal computer|PC game]] and [[Macintosh|Mac]] and in 2016 for [[PlayStation Vita]].\n\n===This Is Abuse===\nIn 2014, McDonnell worked with the [[Home Office]] on their ''This Is Abuse'' Campaign, alongside other prominent YouTubers, in order to educate people about the importance of consensual sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/26545056|title=YouTube vloggers star in new abuse campaign|publisher=BBC  |location=London|accessdate=8 April 2014|date=13 March 2014}}</ref> He also made a video regarding consent on his YouTube channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3GVfesRwvsQ |title=Sex & Consent |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2014-03-20 |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> This campaign by the Home Office came following public discovery of allegiations of sexually abusive behavior committed by British YouTuber Alex Day (an ex-friend/collaborator of McDonnell).{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Production companies==\nIn June 2011, McDonnell founded ''Coollike Productions'' which would become his base for the production of short films and his YouTube channel, according to the online business website [[Duedil]], McDonnell is the company's only director and in May 2013 the company was renamed as ''Qualitea Productions''. It is based in Central London. Reports circulated that a high-level production company wanted to buy the company last year, however, these reports have since been quashed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.duedil.com/company/gb/07685161/qualitea-productions-limited/directors |website=www.duedil.com/|title= Qualitea Productions Limited|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Press==\nMcDonnell was interviewed on [[BBC News]] about his rise to internet stardom. He also participated in the Euro 2008 Zeitgeist [[Google]] conference, where he spoke about YouTube along with [[Mia Rose]] (''miaarose'') and [[Peter Oakley]] (''geriatric1927''). This was a conference to honour online users of popular websites. He featured as a guest on [[Robert Llewellyn]]'s web series ''[[Carpool (web series)|Carpool]]'' in the episode released on 15 May 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebritytweet.com/bobbyllew/link/1361381818/|title=Robert Llewellyn @bobbyllew |quote=This weekend I am shooting a carpool with ''charlieissocoollike''.|publisher=CelebrityTweet!|date=8 February 2018 }}</ref> McDonnell has also made guest appearances on ''[[Lily Allen and Friends]]'' and ''[[The Gadget Show]]''.\n\nMcDonnell was also interviewed for Outlook on the [[BBC World Service]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/programmes/2010/04/100428_outlook_charlie_mcdonnell.shtml|title=The YouTubing teenager getting four million hits a month|quote=Charlie has used the website to broadcast his homemade videos and currently gets an amazing four million hits a month.|publisher=BBC }}</ref> and for an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'' where he talks about the five years of YouTube and his life on the video website.\n\nOn 6 June 2010, McDonnell presented the YouTube Audience Award to [[The Inbetweeners]] as part of the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] Television Awards. In mid-July 2010, McDonnell appeared on KTLA with [[Hank Green]], known on YouTube as one of the [[Vlogbrothers]], and [[iJustine]] to promote VidCon 2010, the first international conference for online video makers. That October he made a programme with [[James Max]] of [[LBC 97.3]] about how to make money on the internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lbc.audioagain.com/index.php?sid=1&player=showchannel&channel_id=349|title=James Max speaks to Charlie McDonnell \u2013 3 Oct 10|quote=Listen back to the Business Hour with James Max as he was joined by the most popular YouTuber in the UK \u2013 Charlie McDonnell, AKA Charlie Is So Cool Like.|publisher=LBC Podcasts}}</ref> In December 2010, McDonnell filmed a series of behind the scenes videos for ''[[Doctor Who Confidential]]'' during the filming of the ''Doctor Who'' Christmas special [[A Christmas Carol (Doctor Who)|A Christmas Carol]].\n\nMcDonnell was purportedly approached to be a Housemate on the eighth series, and first revived series of ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (UK TV series)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' but declined the offer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/coollike/status/104287671916044289|title=Twitter / @coollike: I would like to...|website=Twitter.com}}</ref>\n\nAstronomer [[Phil Plait]] wrote an article for Slate.com (\"Charlie Talks Saturn,\" 8 December 2012) to rave about McDonnell's ongoing series of science videos, including \"Fun Science: Saturn,\" on which Plait gave him some assistance.  Plait found McDonnell to be a \"science nerd\" and a \"really nice guy\" who makes \"engaging, silly and fun\" videos that reach lots of young people who \"need to find their own love of science.\"\n\nA 13 February 2013, New York Times article, \"Blogging with Video, Hoping to Go Viral,\" noted that McDonnell, described as \"a musician and professed nerd with soulful eyes\", has 1.8 million subscribers to [his] video blog or vlog.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|nm3726055}}\n\n{{Chartjackers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonnell, Charlie}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Chartjackers]]\n[[Category:DFTBA Records creators]]\n[[Category:English atheists]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Canada]]\n[[Category:English video bloggers]]\n[[Category:English YouTubers]]\n[[Category:English film directors]]\n[[Category:People educated at Beechen Cliff School]]\n[[Category:People from Bath, Somerset]]\n[[Category:People from Somerset]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly and personal life:Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlie_McDonnell"}
{"title_page": "Narbahadur Thapa", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Naik]]\n| name          = Narbahadur Thapa\n| honorific_suffix = [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)| AC]]\n| image         = \n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| allegiance    = {{Flag|India}}\n| branch        = {{Army|India}}\n| rank          = [[File:Indian Army Naik.gif|30px]] [[Naik]]\n| servicenumber = 10341\n| unit          = [[Gorkha Rifles| 5/5 Gorkha Rifles]]\n| awards        = [[File:Ashoka Chakra ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)| Ashoka Chakra]]\n}}\n\n[[Naik (military rank)|Naik]] Narbahadur Thapa, [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] was a soldier in [[Indian Army]] who was awarded with the first ever peacetime military decoration Award \u201c[[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]]\u201d. He was the first person among the two to receive it for the first time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gallantryawards.gov.in/Awardee/narbahadur-thapa|title=Brave Soldier Narbahadur Thapa|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thankyouindianarmy.com/naik-nar-bahadur-thapa/|title=Naik Narbahadur Thapa Ashoka Chakra Recipient|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n==Military career==\nNaik Narbahadur Thapa was enrolled in Indian Army on 11th November 1940.\nAfter completion his training He got posted to 5/5 [[Gorkha Rifles]]. People explained his personality as a dedicated, brave and trustworthy soldier. Naik Nar Bahadur Thapa\u2019s nature and behavior endeared him to his officer and peer group. In 1948, he was posted in the Hyderabad Police Action for his duties with his battalion. \n==Operation==\nDuring the [[Hyderabad]] Police Action on 13 September 1948, Naik Narbahadur Thapa  was posted with the 5/5 Gorkha Rifles on the field.\nOn the same day, No 2 platoon of A Company,5/5 GR i.e. 5th Battalion the 5th Gorkha Rifles was held up on left flank of the Tungabhadra Railway Bridge in Hyderabad by automatic fire from Ben Gun post and snipping from the other  enemy positions. As soon as the hostile positions were engaged by section fire, Naik Narbahadur Thapa rushed across 100 yards of open ground under heavy enemy fire. He using his khukri and intelligence silenced the machine gun post crew.\nIn doing so Naik Narbahadur Thapa acted with great valor for his duty and nation, he paid no attention to his personal safety and life. By his courageous action, his platoon was able to proceed and secure the vital [[Tungabhadra River|Tungabhadra]] Bridge.\n\n==Ashoka Chakra awardee==\nIn Recognition of his iniative, courage, persoanl bravery, superior leadership and exceptional devotion to his duty in the highest tradition of the Battalion, Naik Narbahadur Thapa was awarded India\u2019s one of the first gallantry awards \u201c[[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashok Chakra]]\u201d.\n\n==Reference==\n<references />\n", "text_old": "Naik Narbahadur Thapa, AC was a soldier in Indian Army who was awarded with the first ever peacetime military decoration Award \u201cAshoka Chakra\u201d. He was the first person among the two to receive it for the first time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gallantryawards.gov.in/Awardee/narbahadur-thapa|title=Brave Soldier Narbahadur Thapa|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thankyouindianarmy.com/naik-nar-bahadur-thapa/|title=Naik Narbahadur Thapa Ashoka Chakra Recipient|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n==Military career==\nNaik Narbahadur Thapa was enrolled in Indian Army on 11th November 1940.\nAfter completion his training He got posted to 5/5 Gorkha Rifles. People explained his personality as a dedicated, brave and trustworthy soldier. Naik Nar Bahadur Thapa\u2019s nature and behavior endeared him to his officer and peer group. In 1948, he was posted in the Hyderabad Police Action for his duties with his battalion. \n==Operation==\nDuring the Hyderabad Police Action on 13 September 1948, Naik Narbahadur Thapa  was posted with the 5/5 Gorkha Rifles on the field.\nOn the same day, No 2 platoon of A Company,5/5 GR i.e. 5th Battalion the 5th Gorkha Rifles was held up on left flank of the Tungabhadra Railway Bridge in Hyderabad by automatic fire from Ben Gun post and snipping from the other  enemy positions. As soon as the hostile positions were engaged by section fire, Naik Narbahadur Thapa rushed across 100 yards of open ground under heavy enemy fire. He using his khukri and intelligence silenced the machine gun post crew.\nIn doing so Naik Narbahadur Thapa acted with great valor for his duty and nation, he paid no attention to his personal safety and life. By his courageous action, his platoon was able to proceed and secure the vital Tungabhadra Bridge.\n\n==Ashoka Chakra awardee==\nIn Recognition of his iniative, courage, persoanl bravery, superior leadership and exceptional devotion to his duty in the highest tradition of the Battalion, Naik Narbahadur Thapa was awarded India\u2019s one of the first gallantry awards \u201cAshok Chakra\u201d.\n\n==Reference==\n<references />\n", "name_user": "Koushik Pain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narbahadur_Thapa"}
{"title_page": "Southern Railway zone", "text_new": "{{short description|Railway zone of Indian Railways}}\n{{Other uses|Southern Railway (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{coord|13.08240|N|80.27705|E|display=title}}\n{{Infobox rail\n| railroad_name     = Southern Railway\n| logo_filename     = \n| logo_size         = 300px\n| system_map        = Indianrailwayzones-numbered.png\n| map_caption       = Southern Railway-7\n| map_size          = \n| marks             = \n| image             = Southern Railway HQ.jpg\n| image_size        =\n| image_caption     = [[Southern Railway headquarters, Chennai]]\n| locale            = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Kerala]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[Karnataka]] and [[Puducherry]]\n| start_year        = {{start date and age|1951}}\n| end_year          =\n| predecessor_line  = [[South Indian Railway Company]]<br />[[Madras and Southern Mahratta Railway]]<br />[[Mysore State Railway]]\n| successor_line    =\n| gauge             = Broad gauge and Metre gauge\n| old_gauge         =\n| electrification   = Yes\n| length            = {{Convert|5081| km}} route<ref>{{cite web|title=Southern Railway vital statistics|url=http://www.sr.indianrailways.gov.in/cris//uploads/files/1547203315572-vital-statistics-2018.pdf|publisher=Southern Railway|accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n| hq_city           = [[Chennai]]\n| website           = {{url|sr.indianrailways.gov.in}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Southern Railway''' (abbreviated '''SR'''), headquartered at [[Chennai]], is one of the 18 zones of [[Indian Railways]]. It is the earliest of the 18 zones of the [[Indian Railways]] created in independent India. It was created on 14 April 1951 by merging three state railways, namely, the [[Madras and Southern Mahratta Railway]], the [[South Indian Railway Company]], and the [[Mysore State Railway]]. The South Indian Railway was originally created in the British colonial times as Great Southern India Railway Co founded in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in 1853 and registered in 1859. Its original headquarters was in [[Tiruchirappalli]] (Trichy) and was registered as a company in [[London]] only in 1890. At present, after re-organization of existing railway zones and creation of new zones undertaken by the Indian Railways between 2002\u201303, Southern Railway has emerged as the 4th largest zone after undertaking some gauge conversion projects and creation of new lines.<ref name=\"srmain\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110031635/http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/thscrip/print.pl?file=2006070300250500.htm&date=2006/07/03/&prd=mp&|title=Origins of Southern Railway|publisher=www.hinduonnet.com|accessdate=17 Jul 2008}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Timeline of Southern Railway zone}}\nIn 1944, all Railway companies were taken over by the Government. And three years later, when India woke up to independence in 1947, the stage was set for the integration of different Railways into smaller zones. In 1948, immediately after independence, there were as many as 42 different railway systems - a multiplicity of railway administrations, varying in size and standards.\n\nThe regrouping proposals put forward by the various committees were studied in great detail to ensure that a unification could be achieved with the least disturbance and dislocation. Important associations of railway-users, Chambers of Commerce and Industry, the State Governments and acknowledged experts both in India and abroad were fully consulted.\n\nShri [[N. Gopalaswami Ayyangar]] - the then Minister for Railways, was the principal architect of the regrouping of Indian Railways. In December 1950, the Central Advisory Committee for Railways approved the plan for Indian Railways into six Zonal systems, namely, the Northern, the North-Eastern, the Southern, the Central, the Eastern and the Western.\n\nThe Southern Railway zone {{convert|9654|km}} was the first zone to be formed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Origins and history of Southern Railway|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/12705/10/10_chapter%202.pdf|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref> Created on 14 April 1951 by the merger of the Madras and Southern Mahratta Railway, the South Indian Railway and the Mysore State Railway, the economic and geographical factors of this zone facilitated an early integrated network. This amalgamation was a major step towards streamlining and organizing the working pattern of the Railway system.\n\nShri K R Ramanujam was appointed the first General Manager of the newly formed Southern Railways.\n\n==Organisation==\nThe Southern Railway is headed by the General Manager (HAG+) Officer, assisted by an Additional General Manager (HAG). Each department is headed by a PHOD\\CHOD of the rank of HAG\\SAG.\n\n==Jurisdiction==\nSouthern Railway has its headquarters in Chennai and has the following six divisions: \n#{{rwd|Chennai}}\n#{{rwd|Madurai}}\n#{{rwd|Palakkad}}\n#{{rwd|Salem}}\n#{{rwd|Thiruvananthapuram}}\n#{{rwd|Tiruchirappalli}}\n\nIt covers the states of [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Kerala]], [[Puducherry]] and small portions of [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Karnataka]]. More than 50 [[crore]] passengers travel on the network every year.\n\n== Operations ==\nThe zone operates both passenger and freight trains. The biggest station of the Zone is [[Puratchi Thalaivar Dr. M.G. Ramachandran Central Railway Station]]. Other major stations of the Zone includes [[Chennai Egmore railway station|Chennai Egmore]], Arakkonam Junction, Vellore Katpadi Junction, [[Mangalore Central railway station|Mangalore Central]], [[Mangalore Junction railway station|Mangalore Jn.]], [[Coimbatore Junction railway station|Coimbatore]], [[Salem Junction|Salem]], [[Palakkad Junction railway station|Palakkad]], [[Kozhikode railway station|Kozhikode]], [[Viluppuram Junction|Viluppuram]], [[Ernakulam Junction railway station|Ernakulam]] Junction, [[Kottayam Railway Station]],  [[Madurai Junction railway station|Madurai]], [[Tirunelveli Junction railway station|Tirunelveli]], [[Tiruchirappalli Junction railway station|Trichy]], [[Thiruvananthapuram Central railway station|Thiruvananthapuram Central]], [[Kochuveli railway station|Trivandrum Kochuveli]], [[Nagercoil Junction railway station|Nagercoil Junction]], Jolarpettai Junction , [[Erode Junction|Erode]], [[Kollam Junction Railway Station|Kollam]], [[Thrissur Railway Station|Thrissur]], [[Kannur Railway Station|Kannur]], [[Shoranur Junction railway station|Shoranur]], and [[Puducherry railway station|Puducherry]]. Passenger trains range from day intercity trains to overnight trains, long-distance trains to other zones, [[Shatabdi Express|Shatabdi]] and passenger trains stopping at many stations. The zone owns a large number of coaches.  These are maintained at coach care centres. Basin Bridge coach care centre serving Chennai central is one of the biggest in the country. Most major stations have a coach care Centre. The stations which don't have such facilities are served by trains through sometimes complex rake-sharing arrangements which also increases the utilization of the coaches. Apart from these Centres, the zone has MEMU and DEMU car sheds. These are available in Avadi, Trichy, Erode, Palakkad and Kollam. The zone also operates [[Chennai Suburban Railway|suburban system in Chennai]].\n\nFreight operations mainly include container traffic from all the ports falling under its jurisdiction ( [[Chennai Port|Chennai]], [[New Mangalore Port|Mangalore]], [[Ennore Port|Ennore]], [[Cochin Port|Cochin]] and [[Tuticorin Port Trust|Tuticorin]] are some of the major ports) and coal-traffic bound to the thermal power stations in Tamil  Nadu state from the ports. Public sector oil companies also transport petroleum products from refineries to storage terminals using the zone. Cement plants also use the railway system extensively. Food grains are also transported through freight trains. Most of the lines inside ports, thermal stations, manufacturing industries and owned by the respective companies and the zone provides a link connecting its network and the wagons and locomotives. There is a wagon care centre in Tondiarpet, Chennai.\n\nThe zone has electric loco sheds at Royapuram, Erode and Arakkonam. Diesel loco sheds are present at Tondiarpet, Golden Rock, Ernakulam and Erode.  Most of the important routes are electrified and only low traffic lines are unelectrified. However, it is common to see diesel locos in electrified lines due to various operational constraints. It is also common to see other zones' locomotives operating inside the zone and vice versa.\n\nSince the zone has little freight traffic compared to other zones and huge passenger traffic (which are run at low fares across the country), the zones' finances are often in a bad shape.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/southern-railway-punctuality-and-fiscal-performance-hit/articleshow/62666618.cms|title=Southern Railway punctuality and fiscal performance hit - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/southern-railways-financial-and-operational-performance-dips/articleshow/60077695.cms|title=Southern Railway\u2019s financial and operational performance dips - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n=== Assets ===\n\nSouthern Railway has many factories & sheds:\n* '''Mechanical Workshops'''\n** Carriage, Wagon and Loco Works, Perambur, Chennai\n** [[Golden Rock Railway Workshop|Central Workshop, Ponmalai, Tiruchirapalli]]\n** Engineering Work Shop, Arakkonam\n* '''Signal & Telecommunication Workshop'''\n** Southern Railway Signal & Telecom Workshop, Podanur, Coimbatore\n* '''Sheds'''\n** Locomotive Sheds\n*** Diesel\n**** [[Diesel Loco Shed, Golden Rock]], [[Tiruchirapalli]]\n**** Diesel Loco Shed, [[Tondiarpet]], [[Chennai]]\n**** [[Diesel Loco Shed, Erode]]\n**** [[Diesel Loco Shed, Ernakulam]]\n*** Electrical\n**** Electrical Loco Shed, [[Arakkonam]]\n**** Electrical Loco Shed, [[Erode]]\n**** Electrical Loco Shed, [[Royapuram]], Chennai\n*** Steam Loco Shed\n**** Coonoor, [[The Nilgiris District|The Nilgiris]]\n** [[MEMU]] Car Shed\n*** [[Kollam MEMU Shed|MEMU Car Shed]], [[Kollam]]\n*** [[MEMU]] Car Shed, [[Palakkad]]\n** EMU Car Shed\n*** EMU Car Shed, Avadi \n*** EMU Car Shed, Tambaram\n*** EMU Car Shed,Velachery\n** '''BG Coaching Maintenance Depots'''\n*** [[Basin Bridge]], [[Chennai]]\n*** [[Egmore]], [[Chennai]]\n*** [[Madurai]]\n*** [[Salem, Tamil Nadu|Salem]]\n*** [[Erode]]\n*** [[Coimbatore]]\n*** [[Mettupalayam, Coimbatore|Mettupalayam]]\n*** [[Shoranur]]\n*** [[Mangalore]] central\n*** [[Thiruvananthapuram]]\n*** [[Ernakulam]]\n*** [[Kollam]]\n*** [[Tirunelveli]]\n*** [[Nagercoil]]\n*** [[Rameswaram]]\n*** [[Thoothukudi]]\n*** [[Tiruchirapalli]]\n*** [[Viluppuram]]\n*** [[Tambaram]]\n** '''Wagon Maintenance Depots'''\n*** Tondiarpet, Chennai\n*** Egmore, Chennai\n*** Madurai\n*** Jolarpettai\n*** Kochi Harbour\n*** [[Arakkonam]]\n*** Royapuram, Chennai\n*** Pattibiram Military Siding\n*** Erode\n*** [[Mangalore]] junction\n*** Ernakulam\n*** Milavittan\n*** Irumpanam\n*** Tiruchirapalli\n*** Viluppuram\n*** Uthagamandalam\n* '''Printing Presses'''\n** General Printing Press, Royapuram, Chennai\n** Ticket Printing Factory, Thiruvananthapuram,\n** Ticket Printing Factory, Tiruchirappalli\n\n=== Rail transport ===\n==== Surveys ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!! style=\"background-color:#FFD700\" | Route\n!! style=\"background-color:#FFD700\" | State\n!! style=\"background-color:#FFD700\" | Length in km\n|-\n\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |Bulb rail line at Shoranur\n| valign=\"top\" |Kerala\n| valign=\"top\" |5\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |Sabrimala-Chengannur\n| valign=\"top\" |Kerala\n| valign=\"top\" |64\n|-\n\n\n\n|-\n\n|-\n| \n\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |Morappur-Dharmapuri via Mukkanur\n| valign=\"top\" |Tamil Nadu\n| valign=\"top\" |36\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |Needmangalam-Pattukottai 