eering-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CamWass", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar/spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elisabeth_Ingvaldsen"}
{"title_page": "The Rectory School", "text_new": "{{short description|School in Pomfret, Connecticut, US}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name = Rectory School\n|image = Rectory School.jpg\n|motto = ''Respect, Responsibility, Honesty, and Compassion''\n|established = 1920\n|type = [[Independent school|Independent]], [[Boarding school|Boarding]]\n|head_name = Headmaster\n|head = Frederick W. Williams\n|city = [[Pomfret, Connecticut|Pomfret]]\n|state = [[Connecticut]]\n|country = United States\n|campus = Zoom\n|grades = K-9\n|enrollment = 230\n|faculty = 65\n|ratio = 4:1\n|colors = <span style=\"color:black; background:orange\">Black and Orange</span>\n|newspaper = The DiRectory\n|homepage = {{URL|http://www.rectoryschool.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Rectory School''' is an independent, coeducational, junior boarding (5\u20139) and day school (K\u20139) in [[Pomfret, Connecticut]], United States. The school was founded by Rev. Frank H. Bigelow in 1920.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitylimerock.org/history/past_clergy.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722050703/http://www.trinitylimerock.org/history/past_clergy.htm |archivedate=2011-07-22 }}</ref> Ever since, it has expanded to {{convert|138|acre|km2}}, 26 buildings, 250 students, and 65 faculty members, as of 2017. \n\n'''Current Status''' The 138-acre Connecticut campus currently serves 9 students. The rest attend online classes from all over the United States and the world. \n\n'''Unwritten Rule''' If you are a varsity A basketball player, you are allowed to sexual harass girls without getting into trouble.\n\nRectory is located on [[Connecticut Route 169]] next to the [[Pomfret School]].\n\n==Academics==\nThe Individualized Instruction Program (IIP) was pioneered by Rectory School and benefits the students by daily, one-to-one or small-group assistance and enrichment. Meeting within the regular rotation of classes during the academic day, students develop skills in written and spoken language, reading comprehension, mathematics, English as a foreign language, and study habits. Students' IIP is tailored to their interests and aptitudes, so students may pursue independent study, explore enrichment activities, or receive subject support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rectoryschool.org/academics|title=Academics - Rectory School|website=www.rectoryschool.org}}</ref>\n\nThe School embraces creativity.  All students are involved in music, either in classes or private lessons.  Moreover, the performing and visual arts courses are enhanced by excellent facilities.  Everyone also takes part in sports on levels that test the skilled athlete and encourage the beginner.\n\nThe Rectory School is accredited by the Connecticut Association of Independent Schools (CAIS), the National Association for the Education of Young Children (NAEYC), and approved by the [[Connecticut]] State Board of Education. Memberships include the [[National Association of Independent Schools]] (NAIS) The Connecticut Association of Independent Schools (CAIS) and [[The Association of Boarding Schools]] (TABS).  Rectory is a member of [[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC).\n\nNearly 20 years ago, Mr. Brad Seaward, jumped at the opportunity to combine two passions of his: basketball and community outreach. The result was the School's Hoops for Hunger program.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Robert Ludlum]] - Author, best known for the [[Jason Bourne]] novels\n*[[Owsley (musician)|William Reese \"Will\" Owsley III]] - Musician known as [[Owsley (musician)|Owsley]]\n*[[Peter L. Pond]] - Clergyman, activist and philanthropist\n*[[Julian Roosevelt]] - Olympic Gold Medalist\n*[[Oscar Tang]] - Philanthropist to Rectory and other schools and universities\n*[[Gabriel Traversari]] - actor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.rectoryschool.org/ }}\n{{coord|41.894|-71.9631|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rectory School}}\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Schools in Windham County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Pomfret, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|School in Pomfret, Connecticut, US}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name = Rectory School\n|image = Rectory School.jpg\n|motto = ''Respect, Responsibility, Honesty, and Compassion''\n|established = 1920\n|type = [[Independent school|Independent]], [[Boarding school|Boarding]]\n|head_name = Headmaster\n|head = Frederick W. Williams\n|city = [[Pomfret, Connecticut|Pomfret]]\n|state = [[Connecticut]]\n|country = United States\n|campus = Zoom\n|grades = K-9\n|enrollment = 230\n|faculty = 65\n|ratio = 4:1\n|colors = <span style=\"color:black; background:orange\">Black and Orange</span>\n|newspaper = The DiRectory\n|homepage = {{URL|http://www.rectoryschool.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Rectory School''' is an independent, coeducational, junior boarding (5\u20139) and day school (K\u20139) in [[Pomfret, Connecticut]], United States. The school was founded by Rev. Frank H. Bigelow in 1920.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitylimerock.org/history/past_clergy.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722050703/http://www.trinitylimerock.org/history/past_clergy.htm |archivedate=2011-07-22 }}</ref> Ever since, it has expanded to {{convert|138|acre|km2}}, 26 buildings, 250 students, and 65 faculty members, as of 2017. \n\n'''Current Status''' The 138-acre Connecticut campus currently serves 9 students. The rest attend online classes from all over the United States and the world. \n\nRectory is located on [[Connecticut Route 169]] next to the [[Pomfret School]].\n\n==Academics==\nThe Individualized Instruction Program (IIP) was pioneered by Rectory School and benefits the students by daily, one-to-one or small-group assistance and enrichment. Meeting within the regular rotation of classes during the academic day, students develop skills in written and spoken language, reading comprehension, mathematics, English as a foreign language, and study habits. Students' IIP is tailored to their interests and aptitudes, so students may pursue independent study, explore enrichment activities, or receive subject support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rectoryschool.org/academics|title=Academics - Rectory School|website=www.rectoryschool.org}}</ref>\n\nThe School embraces creativity.  All students are involved in music, either in classes or private lessons.  Moreover, the performing and visual arts courses are enhanced by excellent facilities.  Everyone also takes part in sports on levels that test the skilled athlete and encourage the beginner.\n\nThe Rectory School is accredited by the Connecticut Association of Independent Schools (CAIS), the National Association for the Education of Young Children (NAEYC), and approved by the [[Connecticut]] State Board of Education. Memberships include the [[National Association of Independent Schools]] (NAIS) The Connecticut Association of Independent Schools (CAIS) and [[The Association of Boarding Schools]] (TABS).  Rectory is a member of [[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC).\n\nNearly 20 years ago, Mr. Brad Seaward, jumped at the opportunity to combine two passions of his: basketball and community outreach. The result was the School's Hoops for Hunger program.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Robert Ludlum]] - Author, best known for the [[Jason Bourne]] novels\n*[[Owsley (musician)|William Reese \"Will\" Owsley III]] - Musician known as [[Owsley (musician)|Owsley]]\n*[[Peter L. Pond]] - Clergyman, activist and philanthropist\n*[[Julian Roosevelt]] - Olympic Gold Medalist\n*[[Oscar Tang]] - Philanthropist to Rectory and other schools and universities\n*[[Gabriel Traversari]] - actor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.rectoryschool.org/ }}\n{{coord|41.894|-71.9631|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rectory School}}\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Schools in Windham County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Pomfret, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "2601:192:4d00:7e30:fc17:55a:c33:ddae", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Rectory_School"}
{"title_page": "Charlie Condou", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Charlie Condou\n| birth_name   = Charles Lomax David Condou\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1973|01|08|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n| occupation   = [[Actor]], [[writer]]\n| years_active = 1986\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Cameron Laux|2015}}\n| children     = 2 \n| residence    =\n| television   = [[Nathan Barley]] <br />[[Coronation Street]]\n}}\n'''Charlie Condou''', (born 8 January 1973) is a British actor, columnist and LGBT rights activist. Condou secured a series of television movie roles during his teenage years in the 1980s. He later had guest roles in British television series during the 1990s. In 2007, Condou gained wider recognition when he took the role of sonographer [[Marcus Dent]] in the soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'', which he remained until 2014. He currently plays the role of [[Ben Sherwood (Holby City)|Ben Sherwood]] in the medical drama ''[[Holby City]]''. Condou has used his fame as a platform to promote LGBT rights, becoming a patron for charities and being an advocate for same-sex parenting.\n\n==Career==\nCondou's acting career began in the 1985 American television Movie, ''[[The Key to Rebecca]]'' as Billy Vandam. Billy is the young son of the main character William, played by [[Cliff Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Kay|last=Gardella|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42962967/|title=Cliff Robertson: again, a star|date=28 April 1985|work=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=25 January 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{free access}}</ref> He then appeared in the 1985 movie ''Exploits at West Poley'' at the age of twelve. His television career continued throughout his teens with appearances in the shows ''[[Robin of Sherwood]]'' and ''A Sense of Guilt''. In 1988, Condou appeared in the television movie ''Every Breath You Take'' as a thirteen year old chorister. He worked with actress [[Connie Booth]] who played his on-screen mother in the movie.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sandy|last=Smithies|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42962180/the_guardian/|title=Watching brief|date=9 April 1988|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=25 January 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{free access}}</ref> He went onto secure the role of Stuart Wolvis in the six part British comedy drama series ''The Wolvis Family''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42962372/|title=Green guide - Tuesday|date=6 May 1993|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=25 January 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{free access}}</ref> The show focuses on the Wolvis' family issues, with Stuart being the problematic teenager of the family.<ref>{{cite news|first=Raymond|last=Gill|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42962451/|title=Comedy on the couch|date=6 May 1993|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=25 January 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{free access}}</ref> He continued in his twenties, playing a variety of roles in series like ''[[Martin Chuzzlewit]]'', ''[[Pie in the Sky (TV series)|Pie in the Sky]]'', ''[[The Bill]]'', ''[[Peak Practice]]'', ''[[Urban Gothic]]'', ''[[The Infinite Worlds of H. G. Wells]]'' and ''[[Midsomer Murders]]''.<ref name=main/> Other roles included a guest appearances as Nino in television series ''[[Gimme Gimme Gimme (TV series)|Gimme, Gimme, Gimme]]'' alongside [[Kathy Burke]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Gimme Gimme Gimme |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/gimme-gimme-gimme-20040416-gdiqrj.html |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=([[Fairfax Media]]) |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=16 April 2004}}</ref> and Giles in the film ''[[Dead Babies (film)|Dead Babies]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradshaw |first1=Peter |title=Dead Babies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/jan/26/martinamis.film |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=26 January 2001}}</ref> He then played the role of Auguste in the 2001 thriller film ''[[Charlotte Gray (film)|Charlotte Gray]]'' alongside [[Cate Blanchett]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Todd |title=Charlotte Gray |url=https://variety.com/2001/film/reviews/charlotte-gray-2-1200552230/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=16 December 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the actor played editor Jonatton Yeah? in the [[Channel 4]] sitcom ''[[Nathan Barley]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mansell |first1=Tom |title=Nathan Barley: 10 years on |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/tube-talk-gold/a399600/nathan-barley-is-10-looking-back-at-charlie-brookers-debut-tv-series/ |website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hearst Magazines UK]]) |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=11 February 2015}}</ref> In 2006, Condou appeared as [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]] in the [[BBC]] drama ''[[The Impressionists (BBC drama)|The Impressionists]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crawford |first1=Sue |title='I had a girlfriend in my 20s... just like Marcus and Maria': Charlie Condou says Coronation Street storyline is more true-to-life than you'd think |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/coronation-street-charlie-condou-aka-1412224 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]]) |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=2 November 2012}}</ref> He had a cameo role as an elf in the film ''[[Fred Claus]]''. In 2007, Condou joined the cast of the British soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'', playing [[Marcus Dent]]. In 2008 he left the show and stated that \"I have had a fantastic time in Coronation Street, but as a jobbing actor I believe it is time to move on.\" A publicist from the show added \"we'll be sad to see Charlie leave.\"<ref name=\"mirror1\">{{cite web |title=Coronation Street star Charlie Condou to leave the soap |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/coronation-street-star-charlie-condou-302211 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=10 April 2008}}</ref> At the time, Condou indicated that \"there are a few things in the pipeline, one of which is a feature film which is being made abroad. But all that's under wraps at the moment.\" This film turned out to be ''[[Good (film)|Good]]'', released later that year.<ref name=\"mirror1\"/>\n\nIn 2013, it was announced that Condou would be leaving Coronation Street the following year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=Corrie actor quits Marcus Dent role |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s3/coronation-street/news/a533918/coronation-street-star-charlie-condou-quits-marcus-dent-role.html |website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hearst Magazines UK]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=26 November 2013}}</ref> In September 2014, he took the lead role of Adam in the West End production of \"Next Fall\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Jane |title=Next Fall (Southwark Playhouse) {{!}} WhatsOnStage |url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/reviews/next-fall-southwark-playhouse_35921.html |website=[[WhatsOnStage.com]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=30 September 2014}}</ref> From September to December 2016, he took part in the UK tour of ''The Rocky Horror Show''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charlie Condou talks Rocky Horror |url=https://www.itv.com/lorraine/showbiz/charlie-condou-talks-rocky-horror |website=[[itv.com]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=15 September 2016}}</ref> In February 2017, Condou played Reverend Hale in the UK tour of Arthur Miller's play The Crucible.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Longman |first1=Will |title=Exclusive: Charlie Condou to star in The Crucible |url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/birmingham-theatre/news/exclusive-charlie-condou-cast-the-crucible-uk-tour_42058.html |website=[[WhatsOnStage.com]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=30 October 2016}}</ref> That year, he was cast in the role of Simon Osborne in the second series of the ITV drama ''[[Unforgotten]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gardner |first1=Alison |title=The murder mystery that has put former Corrie star Charlie Condou back on TV |url=https://www.whatsontv.co.uk/coronation-street-home/corrie-news/charlie-condou-thriller-tv-447619/ |website=[[What's on TV]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Condou joined the cast of ''[[Holby City]]'' in a guest role, playing doctor [[Ben Sherwood (Holby City)|Ben Sherwood]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dainty |first1=Sophie |title=Exclusive: Corrie's Charlie Condou speaks out on his Holby City debut tonight |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/holby-city/a30279694/holby-city-charlie-condou-ben-sherwood-big-story/ |website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hearst Magazines UK]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCondou is openly gay, and married his long-term [[Canada|Canadian]] boyfriend Cameron Laux on 8 June 2015.<ref name=\"Leyfield\">{{cite news |last1=Leyfield |first1=James |title=Ex-Coronation Street star Charlie Condou marries partner Cameron Laux |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/charlie-condou-cameron-laux-marry-5850679 |accessdate=10 February 2019 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]])|date=9 June 2015}}</ref> He lives in [[Islington]] with his husband and his children,<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview: Charlie Condou talks about leaving Coronation Street and being a gay parent |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/01/06/interview-charlie-condou-talks-about-leaving-coronation-street-and-being-a-gay-parent/ |website=[[PinkNews]] |accessdate=28 February 2020 |date=6 January 2014}}</ref> Georgia and Hal, who split their time between him and their mother, the actress Catherine Kanter. Condou and Kanter first met in 1998 and made a mutual agreement between each other that they would have a child if she was still single at the age of forty.<ref name=\"Leyfield\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Morgan |first1=Joe |title=Charlie Condou set to marry partner of 10 years today |url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/charlie-condou-set-marry-partner-10-years-today080615/#gs.2n3UGekH |website=Gay Star News |accessdate=10 February 2019 |date=8 June 2015}}</ref> In a number of interviews, Condou has revealed that the children were conceived through IVF treatment, following Kanter's fortieth birthday and relationship breakup.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronation Street's Charlie Condou on why he's delighted to be returning to Weatherfield to play a gay dad |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/coronation-streets-charlie-condou-on-why-hes-135880#ixzz1PiO80b8O |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=19 January 2011}}</ref> From October 2011 until July 2012, he wrote a  column for ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper on the subject of same-sex parenting.\n\nCondou supported the UK remaining a member of the European Union in the [[2016 EU referendum]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/oct/01/coronation-street-charlie-condou-gay-dad?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Charlie | last=Condou | title=Charlie Condou: My real 'gay celebrity dad' life | date=1 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Charlie Condou |url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/charlie-condou |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=24 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nCondou has been listed on LGBT influence lists and polls during his career. He was listed at number fifteen in the World Pride Power List 2012 and rose to number eleven on the 2013 list.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jolin |first1=Lucy |last2=Delgado |first2=Chance |title=World Pride Power List 2012: 100 most influential LGBT people of the year |url=https://www.theguardian.com/careers/world-pride-power-list-2012-11-to-100 |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=bio/> Additionally he was placed eighth on ''[[The Independent|The Independent's]]'' Pink Power list 2011<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Ian |title=The IoS Pink List 2011 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/the-ios-pink-list-2011-2374595.html |website=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=23 October 2011}}</ref> and forty-second on the Pride Power List of 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introducing the Pride Power List 2011 |url=http://www.pridepowerlist.co.uk/index.html |website=pridepowerlist.co.uk |accessdate=8 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607025700/http://www.pridepowerlist.co.uk/index.html |archivedate=7 June 2012}}</ref> He is a patron of the charities Diversity Role Models and the [[Albert Kennedy Trust]], and has volunteered for the [[Terrence Higgins Trust]].<ref>[http://www.tht.org.uk/mediacentre/pressreleases/2011/november/november2.htm THT: Media Centre: News and press releases: 2011: November<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108010545/http://www.tht.org.uk/mediacentre/pressreleases/2011/november/november2.htm |date=8 November 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Patrons |url=https://www.diversityrolemodels.org/about-us/patrons |website=diversityrolemodels.org |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref> Condou has also worked with Stonewall on fundraisers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregory |first1=Katie |title=TV stars and Mayor support Brighton gay equality walk |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/9011326.tv-stars-and-mayor-support-brighton-gay-equality-walk/ |website=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]] |accessdate=24 January 2020 |date=5 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stonewall sets sail and raises over \u00a364,000 for LGBT equality |url=https://www.stonewallscotland.org.uk/news/stonewall-sets-sail-and-raises-over-\u00a364000-lgbt-equality |website=[[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]] |accessdate=24 January 2020 |date=16 June 2015}}</ref> In October 2012, he was named in the British gay publication, ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'', as the magazine's \"Man of the Year\" at the inaugural ''Attitude'' awards and appeared on the cover of the November 2012 issue.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charlie Condou |url=http://www.diversityinmediaawards.com/charlie-condou.html |website=Diversity In Media Awards |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref> In 2014 he was nominated for the \"Advocate for change\" award at the [[GLAAD]] awards in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Ross |title=GLAAD Global Voices: Charlie Condou is a gay parent who advocates for LGBT youth |url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/glaad-global-voices-charlie-condou-gay-parent-who-advocates-lgbt-youth |website=[[GLAAD]] |accessdate=24 January 2020 |date=1 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nCondou has also been an advocate for LGBT families. In 2013, he set up the company, Out With the Family, which puts on events for LGBT families.<ref name=bio>{{Cite web|url=https://prideinlondon.org/news-and-views/pride-in-london-launches-exclusive-lgbt-miniseries/|title=Pride in London launches exclusive LGBT+ miniseries|website=Pride in London|language=en-GB|access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref> In 2016, Condou wrote the introduction for Eric Rosswood's ''[[Journey to Same-Sex Parenthood: Firsthand Advice, Tips and Stories from Lesbian and Gay Couples]]''.<ref name=\"New Horitzon Press\">{{cite web|title=Journey to Same-Sex Parenthood|url=http://www.newhorizonpressbooks.com/sh-parenting/journey-to-same-sex-parenthood.php|website=New Horitzon Press|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref> In December 2019, Condou spoke at a seminar focusing on \"non-traditional families\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Seminar Set To Put Families Streets Ahead On LGBT Parenting |url=https://www.irwinmitchell.com/newsandmedia/2019/november/seminar-set-to-put-families-streets-ahead-on-lgbt-parenting |website=irwinmitchell.com |accessdate=24 January 2020 |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Condou was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' opposing [[Scottish independence]] in the run-up to September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories &#124; Politics |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014|newspaper=[[The Guardian]] }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1985\n| ''[[The Key to Rebecca]]''\n| Billy Vandam\n| TV movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1985\n| ''Exploits at West Poley''\n| Leonard\n| TV movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1986\n| ''[[Robin of Sherwood]]''\n| Martin\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| ''Every Breath You Take''\n| Tom\n| TV movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| ''[[The Storyteller (TV series)|The Storyteller]]''\n| Brother 2\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| ''[[To Kill a Priest]]''\n| Mirek\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1991 \n| ''A Sense of Guilt''\n| Peter Murray\n| Recurring role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1991 \n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| David Williamson\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1991 \n| ''The Wolvis Family''\n| Stuart Wolvis\n| Regular role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1992\n| ''[[Eldorado]]''\n| Clive Mitchell\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1993\n| ''Frank Stubbs Promotes''\n| Jason Stubbs\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1994\n| ''[[Martin Chuzzlewit]]''\n| Footman\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1994\n| ''[[The Bill]]''\n| Michael Kenyon\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1995 \n| ''Casualty''\n| Cal McGregor\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1995\n| ''[[Pie in the Sky (TV series)|Pie in the Sky]]''\n| Karl Elves\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1995\n| ''The Bill''\n| Steve Downing\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1999\n| ''[[Gimme Gimme Gimme (TV series)|Gimme Gimme Gimme]]''\n| Nino\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1999\n| ''[[Peak Practice]]''\n| Private Benedict Grinter\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1999\n| ''Honky Sausages''\n| O.G.\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2000\n| ''[[Urban Gothic (TV series)|Urban Gothic]]''\n| Lenny\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2000\n| ''[[Dead Babies (film)|Dead Babies]]''\n| Giles\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2001\n| ''[[The Infinite Worlds of H. G. Wells]]''\n| Sam\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2001\n| ''[[Charlotte Gray (film)|Charlotte Gray]]''\n| Auguste\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2003\n| ''[[Trust (British TV series)|Trust]]''\n| Max\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| ''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n| Jake Foley\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| ''[[Nathan Barley]]''\n| Jonatton Yeah?\n| Regular role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| ''[[Secret Smile]]''\n| Lawrence\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2006\n| ''[[The Impressionists (BBC drama)|The Impressionists]]''\n| Renoir\n| Recurring role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2007\n| ''Flirting with Flamenco''\n| Warren\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2007\n| ''[[Fred Claus]]''\n| Elf\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2007\n| ''[[Holby City]]''\n| Tony Butler\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2007\u201308, 2011\u201314\n| ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n| [[Marcus Dent]]\n| Regular role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2008\n| ''[[Good (film)|Good]]''\n| Bekemeier\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2009 \n| ''Casualty''\n| Gal\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2016\n| ''[[You, Me and the Apocalypse]]''\n| Father Alphonse\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2017\n| ''[[Unforgotten]]''\n| Simon Osborne\n| Regular role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2019-2020\n| ''[[Holby City]]''\n| [[Ben Sherwood (Holby City)|Ben Sherwood]]\n| Recurring role\n|-\n|}\n\n:<small>Sources:<ref name=main>{{cite web |title=Charlie Condou |url=https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/cv/10204/acting |website=United Agents |accessdate=25 January 2020}}</ref></small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0003626}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Condou, Charlie}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT journalists from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from England]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Charlie Condou\n| birth_name   = Charles Lomax David Condou\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1973|01|08|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n| occupation   = [[Actor]], [[writer]]\n| years_active = 1986\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Cameron Laux|2015}}\n| children     = 2 \n| residence    =\n| television   = [[Nathan Barley]] <br />[[Coronation Street]]\n}}\n'''Charlie Condou''', (born 8 January 1973) is a British actor, columnist and LGBT rights activist. Condou secured a series of television movie roles during his teenage years in the 1980s. He later had guest roles in British television series during the 1990s. In 2007, Condou gained wider recognition when he took the role of sonographer [[Marcus Dent]] in the soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'', which he remained until 2014. He currently plays the role of [[Ben Sherwood (Holby City)|Ben Sherwood]] in the medical drama ''[[Holby City]]''. Condou has used his fame as a platform to promote LGBT rights, becoming a patron for charities and being an advocate for same-sex parenting.\n\n==Career==\nCondou's acting career began in the 1985 American television Movie, ''[[The Key to Rebecca]]'' as Billy Vandam. Billy is the young son of the main character William, played by [[Cliff Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Kay|last=Gardella|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42962967/|title=Cliff Robertson: again, a star|date=28 April 1985|work=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=25 January 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{free access}}</ref> He then appeared in the 1985 movie ''Exploits at West Poley'' at the age of twelve. His television career continued throughout his teens with appearances in the shows ''[[Robin of Sherwood]]'' and ''A Sense of Guilt''. In 1988, Condou appeared in the television movie ''Every Breath You Take'' as a thirteen year old chorister. He worked with actress [[Connie Booth]] who played his on-screen mother in the movie.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sandy|last=Smithies|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42962180/the_guardian/|title=Watching brief|date=9 April 1988|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=25 January 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{free access}}</ref> He went onto secure the role of Stuart Wolvis in the six part British comedy drama series ''The Wolvis Family''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42962372/|title=Green guide - Tuesday|date=6 May 1993|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=25 January 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{free access}}</ref> The show focuses on the Wolvis' family issues, with Stuart being the problematic teenager of the family.<ref>{{cite news|first=Raymond|last=Gill|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42962451/|title=Comedy on the couch|date=6 May 1993|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=25 January 2020|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{free access}}</ref> He continued in his twenties, playing a variety of roles in series like ''[[Martin Chuzzlewit]]'', ''[[Pie in the Sky (TV series)|Pie in the Sky]]'', ''[[The Bill]]'', ''[[Peak Practice]]'', ''[[Urban Gothic]]'', ''[[The Infinite Worlds of H. G. Wells]]'' and ''[[Midsomer Murders]]''.<ref name=main/> Other roles included a guest appearances as Nino in television series ''[[Gimme Gimme Gimme (TV series)|Gimme, Gimme, Gimme]]'' alongside [[Kathy Burke]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Gimme Gimme Gimme |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/gimme-gimme-gimme-20040416-gdiqrj.html |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=([[Fairfax Media]]) |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=16 April 2004}}</ref> and Giles in the film ''[[Dead Babies (film)|Dead Babies]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradshaw |first1=Peter |title=Dead Babies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/jan/26/martinamis.film |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=26 January 2001}}</ref> He then played the role of Auguste in the 2001 thriller film ''[[Charlotte Gray (film)|Charlotte Gray]]'' alongside [[Cate Blanchett]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Todd |title=Charlotte Gray |url=https://variety.com/2001/film/reviews/charlotte-gray-2-1200552230/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=16 December 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the actor played editor Jonatton Yeah? in the [[Channel 4]] sitcom ''[[Nathan Barley]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mansell |first1=Tom |title=Nathan Barley: 10 years on |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/tube-talk-gold/a399600/nathan-barley-is-10-looking-back-at-charlie-brookers-debut-tv-series/ |website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hearst Magazines UK]]) |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=11 February 2015}}</ref> In 2006, Condou appeared as [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]] in the [[BBC]] drama ''[[The Impressionists (BBC drama)|The Impressionists]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crawford |first1=Sue |title='I had a girlfriend in my 20s... just like Marcus and Maria': Charlie Condou says Coronation Street storyline is more true-to-life than you'd think |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/coronation-street-charlie-condou-aka-1412224 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]]) |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=2 November 2012}}</ref> He had a cameo role as an elf in the film ''[[Fred Claus]]''. In 2007, Condou joined the cast of the British soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'', playing [[Marcus Dent]]. In 2008 he left the show and stated that \"I have had a fantastic time in Coronation Street, but as a jobbing actor I believe it is time to move on.\" A publicist from the show added \"we'll be sad to see Charlie leave.\"<ref name=\"mirror1\">{{cite web |title=Coronation Street star Charlie Condou to leave the soap |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/coronation-street-star-charlie-condou-302211 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=10 April 2008}}</ref> At the time, Condou indicated that \"there are a few things in the pipeline, one of which is a feature film which is being made abroad. But all that's under wraps at the moment.\" This film turned out to be ''[[Good (film)|Good]]'', released later that year.<ref name=\"mirror1\"/>\n\nIn 2013, it was announced that Condou would be leaving Coronation Street the following year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kilkelly |first1=Daniel |title=Corrie actor quits Marcus Dent role |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s3/coronation-street/news/a533918/coronation-street-star-charlie-condou-quits-marcus-dent-role.html |website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hearst Magazines UK]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=26 November 2013}}</ref> In September 2014, he took the lead role of Adam in the West End production of \"Next Fall\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Jane |title=Next Fall (Southwark Playhouse) {{!}} WhatsOnStage |url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/reviews/next-fall-southwark-playhouse_35921.html |website=[[WhatsOnStage.com]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=30 September 2014}}</ref> From September to December 2016, he took part in the UK tour of ''The Rocky Horror Show''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charlie Condou talks Rocky Horror |url=https://www.itv.com/lorraine/showbiz/charlie-condou-talks-rocky-horror |website=[[itv.com]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=15 September 2016}}</ref> In February 2017, Condou played Reverend Hale in the UK tour of Arthur Miller's play The Crucible.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Longman |first1=Will |title=Exclusive: Charlie Condou to star in The Crucible |url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/birmingham-theatre/news/exclusive-charlie-condou-cast-the-crucible-uk-tour_42058.html |website=[[WhatsOnStage.com]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=30 October 2016}}</ref> That year, he was cast in the role of Simon Osborne in the second series of the ITV drama ''[[Unforgotten]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gardner |first1=Alison |title=The murder mystery that has put former Corrie star Charlie Condou back on TV |url=https://www.whatsontv.co.uk/coronation-street-home/corrie-news/charlie-condou-thriller-tv-447619/ |website=[[What's on TV]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Condou joined the cast of ''[[Holby City]]'' in a guest role, playing doctor [[Ben Sherwood (Holby City)|Ben Sherwood]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dainty |first1=Sophie |title=Exclusive: Corrie's Charlie Condou speaks out on his Holby City debut tonight |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/holby-city/a30279694/holby-city-charlie-condou-ben-sherwood-big-story/ |website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=([[Hearst Magazines UK]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCondou is openly gay, and married his long-term [[Canada|Canadian]] boyfriend Cameron Laux on 8 June 2015.<ref name=\"Leyfield\">{{cite news |last1=Leyfield |first1=James |title=Ex-Coronation Street star Charlie Condou marries partner Cameron Laux |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/charlie-condou-cameron-laux-marry-5850679 |accessdate=10 February 2019 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]])|date=9 June 2015}}</ref> He lives in [[Islington]] with his husband and his children,<ref>{{cite web |title=Interview: Charlie Condou talks about leaving Coronation Street and being a gay parent |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/01/06/interview-charlie-condou-talks-about-leaving-coronation-street-and-being-a-gay-parent/ |website=[[PinkNews]] |accessdate=28 February 2020 |date=6 January 2014}}</ref> Georgia and Hal, who split their time between him and their mother, the actress Catherine Kanter. Condou and Kanter first met in 1998 and made a mutual agreement between each other that they would have a child if she was still single at the age of forty.<ref name=\"Leyfield\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Morgan |first1=Joe |title=Charlie Condou set to marry partner of 10 years today |url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/charlie-condou-set-marry-partner-10-years-today080615/#gs.2n3UGekH |website=Gay Star News |accessdate=10 February 2019 |date=8 June 2015}}</ref> In a number of interviews, Condou has revealed that the children were conceived through IVF treatment, following Kanter's fortieth birthday and relationship breakup.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronation Street's Charlie Condou on why he's delighted to be returning to Weatherfield to play a gay dad |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/coronation-streets-charlie-condou-on-why-hes-135880#ixzz1PiO80b8O |website=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=19 January 2011}}</ref> From October 2011 until July 2012, he wrote a  column for ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper on the subject of same-sex parenting.\n\nCondou supported the UK remaining a member of the European Union in the [[2016 EU referendum]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/oct/01/coronation-street-charlie-condou-gay-dad?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Charlie | last=Condou | title=Charlie Condou: My real 'gay celebrity dad' life | date=1 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Charlie Condou |url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/charlie-condou |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=24 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nCondou has been listed on LGBT influence lists and polls during his career. He was listed at number fifteen in the World Pride Power List 2012 and rose to number eleven on the 2013 list.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jolin |first1=Lucy |last2=Delgado |first2=Chance |title=World Pride Power List 2012: 100 most influential LGBT people of the year |url=https://www.theguardian.com/careers/world-pride-power-list-2012-11-to-100 |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=bio/> Additionally he was placed eighth on ''[[The Independent|The Independent's]]'' Pink Power list 2011<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herbert |first1=Ian |title=The IoS Pink List 2011 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/the-ios-pink-list-2011-2374595.html |website=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=23 October 2011}}</ref> and forty-second on the Pride Power List of 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introducing the Pride Power List 2011 |url=http://www.pridepowerlist.co.uk/index.html |website=pridepowerlist.co.uk |accessdate=8 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607025700/http://www.pridepowerlist.co.uk/index.html |archivedate=7 June 2012}}</ref> He is a patron of the charities Diversity Role Models and the [[Albert Kennedy Trust]], and has volunteered for the [[Terrence Higgins Trust]].<ref>[http://www.tht.org.uk/mediacentre/pressreleases/2011/november/november2.htm THT: Media Centre: News and press releases: 2011: November<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108010545/http://www.tht.org.uk/mediacentre/pressreleases/2011/november/november2.htm |date=8 November 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Patrons |url=https://www.diversityrolemodels.org/about-us/patrons |website=diversityrolemodels.org |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref> Condou has also worked with Stonewall on fundraisers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregory |first1=Katie |title=TV stars and Mayor support Brighton gay equality walk |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/9011326.tv-stars-and-mayor-support-brighton-gay-equality-walk/ |website=[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Argus]] |accessdate=24 January 2020 |date=5 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stonewall sets sail and raises over \u00a364,000 for LGBT equality |url=https://www.stonewallscotland.org.uk/news/stonewall-sets-sail-and-raises-over-\u00a364000-lgbt-equality |website=[[Stonewall (charity)|Stonewall]] |accessdate=24 January 2020 |date=16 June 2015}}</ref> In October 2012, he was named in the British gay publication, ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'', as the magazine's \"Man of the Year\" at the inaugural ''Attitude'' awards and appeared on the cover of the November 2012 issue.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charlie Condou |url=http://www.diversityinmediaawards.com/charlie-condou.html |website=Diversity In Media Awards |accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref> In 2014 he was nominated for the \"Advocate for change\" award at the [[GLAAD]] awards in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Ross |title=GLAAD Global Voices: Charlie Condou is a gay parent who advocates for LGBT youth |url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/glaad-global-voices-charlie-condou-gay-parent-who-advocates-lgbt-youth |website=[[GLAAD]] |accessdate=24 January 2020 |date=1 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nCondou has also been an advocate for LGBT families. In 2013, he set up the company, Out With the Family, which puts on events for LGBT families.<ref name=bio>{{Cite web|url=https://prideinlondon.org/news-and-views/pride-in-london-launches-exclusive-lgbt-miniseries/|title=Pride in London launches exclusive LGBT+ miniseries|website=Pride in London|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref> In 2016, Condou wrote the introduction for Eric Rosswood's ''[[Journey to Same-Sex Parenthood: Firsthand Advice, Tips and Stories from Lesbian and Gay Couples]]''.<ref name=\"New Horitzon Press\">{{cite web|title=Journey to Same-Sex Parenthood|url=http://www.newhorizonpressbooks.com/sh-parenting/journey-to-same-sex-parenthood.php|website=New Horitzon Press|accessdate=6 May 2018}}</ref> In December 2019, Condou spoke at a seminar focusing on \"non-traditional families\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Seminar Set To Put Families Streets Ahead On LGBT Parenting |url=https://www.irwinmitchell.com/newsandmedia/2019/november/seminar-set-to-put-families-streets-ahead-on-lgbt-parenting |website=irwinmitchell.com |accessdate=24 January 2020 |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Condou was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' opposing [[Scottish independence]] in the run-up to September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories &#124; Politics |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014|newspaper=[[The Guardian]] }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1985\n| ''[[The Key to Rebecca]]''\n| Billy Vandam\n| TV movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1985\n| ''Exploits at West Poley''\n| Leonard\n| TV movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1986\n| ''[[Robin of Sherwood]]''\n| Martin\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| ''Every Breath You Take''\n| Tom\n| TV movie\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| ''[[The Storyteller (TV series)|The Storyteller]]''\n| Brother 2\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| ''[[To Kill a Priest]]''\n| Mirek\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1991 \n| ''A Sense of Guilt''\n| Peter Murray\n| Recurring role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1991 \n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| David Williamson\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1991 \n| ''The Wolvis Family''\n| Stuart Wolvis\n| Regular role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1992\n| ''[[Eldorado]]''\n| Clive Mitchell\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1993\n| ''Frank Stubbs Promotes''\n| Jason Stubbs\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1994\n| ''[[Martin Chuzzlewit]]''\n| Footman\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1994\n| ''[[The Bill]]''\n| Michael Kenyon\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1995 \n| ''Casualty''\n| Cal McGregor\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1995\n| ''[[Pie in the Sky (TV series)|Pie in the Sky]]''\n| Karl Elves\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1995\n| ''The Bill''\n| Steve Downing\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1999\n| ''[[Gimme Gimme Gimme (TV series)|Gimme Gimme Gimme]]''\n| Nino\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1999\n| ''[[Peak Practice]]''\n| Private Benedict Grinter\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1999\n| ''Honky Sausages''\n| O.G.\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2000\n| ''[[Urban Gothic (TV series)|Urban Gothic]]''\n| Lenny\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2000\n| ''[[Dead Babies (film)|Dead Babies]]''\n| Giles\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2001\n| ''[[The Infinite Worlds of H. G. Wells]]''\n| Sam\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2001\n| ''[[Charlotte Gray (film)|Charlotte Gray]]''\n| Auguste\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2003\n| ''[[Trust (British TV series)|Trust]]''\n| Max\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| ''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n| Jake Foley\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| ''[[Nathan Barley]]''\n| Jonatton Yeah?\n| Regular role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| ''[[Secret Smile]]''\n| Lawrence\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2006\n| ''[[The Impressionists (BBC drama)|The Impressionists]]''\n| Renoir\n| Recurring role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2007\n| ''Flirting with Flamenco''\n| Warren\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2007\n| ''[[Fred Claus]]''\n| Elf\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2007\n| ''[[Holby City]]''\n| Tony Butler\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2007\u201308, 2011\u201314\n| ''[[Coronation Street]]''\n| [[Marcus Dent]]\n| Regular role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2008\n| ''[[Good (film)|Good]]''\n| Bekemeier\n| Film\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2009 \n| ''Casualty''\n| Gal\n| Guest role\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2016\n| ''[[You, Me and the Apocalypse